metadata.help:
A tourist destination. In principle any [[Place]] can be a [[TouristDestination]] from a [[City]], [[Region]] or [[Country]] to an [[AmusementPark]] or [[Hotel]]. This Type can be used on its own to describe a general [[TouristDestination]], or be used as an [[additionalType]] to add tourist relevant properties to any other [[Place]].  A [[TouristDestination]] is defined as a [[Place]] that contains, or is colocated with, one or more [[TouristAttraction]]s, often linked by a similar theme or interest to a particular [[touristType]]. The [UNWTO](http://www2.unwto.org/) defines Destination (main destination of a tourism trip) as the place visited that is central to the decision to take the trip.
  (See examples below).

inputs.name: productionDate
inputs.help: The date of production of the item, e.g. vehicle.

inputs.name: gtin13
inputs.help: The GTIN-13 code of the product, or the product to which the offer refers. This is equivalent to 13-digit ISBN codes and EAN UCC-13. Former 12-digit UPC codes can be converted into a GTIN-13 code by simply adding a preceding zero. See [GS1 GTIN Summary](http://www.gs1.org/barcodes/technical/idkeys/gtin) for more details.

inputs.name: awards
inputs.help: Awards won by or for this item.

inputs.name: manufacturer
inputs.help: The manufacturer of the product.

inputs.name: weight
inputs.help: The weight of the product or person.

inputs.name: brand
inputs.help: The brand(s) associated with a product or service, or the brand(s) maintained by an organization or business person.

inputs.name: review
inputs.help: A review of the item.

inputs.name: slogan
inputs.help: A slogan or motto associated with the item.

inputs.name: gtin
inputs.help: A Global Trade Item Number ([GTIN](https://www.gs1.org/standards/id-keys/gtin)). GTINs identify trade items, including products and services, using numeric identification codes. The [[gtin]] property generalizes the earlier [[gtin8]], [[gtin12]], [[gtin13]], and [[gtin14]] properties. The GS1 [digital link specifications](https://www.gs1.org/standards/Digital-Link/) express GTINs as URLs. A correct [[gtin]] value should be a valid GTIN, which means that it should be an all-numeric string of either 8, 12, 13 or 14 digits, or a "GS1 Digital Link" URL based on such a string. The numeric component should also have a [valid GS1 check digit](https://www.gs1.org/services/check-digit-calculator) and meet the other rules for valid GTINs. See also [GS1's GTIN Summary](http://www.gs1.org/barcodes/technical/idkeys/gtin) and [Wikipedia](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Global_Trade_Item_Number) for more details. Left-padding of the gtin values is not required or encouraged.

inputs.name: itemCondition
inputs.help: A predefined value from OfferItemCondition or a textual description of the condition of the product or service, or the products or services included in the offer.

inputs.name: gtin14
inputs.help: The GTIN-14 code of the product, or the product to which the offer refers. See [GS1 GTIN Summary](http://www.gs1.org/barcodes/technical/idkeys/gtin) for more details.

inputs.name: isAccessoryOrSparePartFor
inputs.help: A pointer to another product (or multiple products) for which this product is an accessory or spare part.

inputs.name: reviews
inputs.help: Review of the item.

inputs.name: model
inputs.help: The model of the product. Use with the URL of a ProductModel or a textual representation of the model identifier. The URL of the ProductModel can be from an external source. It is recommended to additionally provide strong product identifiers via the gtin8/gtin13/gtin14 and mpn properties.

inputs.name: material
inputs.help: A material that something is made from, e.g. leather, wool, cotton, paper.

inputs.name: additionalProperty
inputs.help: A property-value pair representing an additional characteristics of the entitity, e.g. a product feature or another characteristic for which there is no matching property in schema.org.\n\nNote: Publishers should be aware that applications designed to use specific schema.org properties (e.g. http://schema.org/width, http://schema.org/color, http://schema.org/gtin13, ...) will typically expect such data to be provided using those properties, rather than using the generic property/value mechanism.

inputs.name: isVariantOf
inputs.help: Indicates the kind of product that this is a variant of. In the case of [[ProductModel]], this is a pointer (from a ProductModel) to a base product from which this product is a variant. It is safe to infer that the variant inherits all product features from the base model, unless defined locally. This is not transitive. In the case of a [[ProductGroup]], the group description also serves as a template, representing a set of Products that vary on explicitly defined, specific dimensions only (so it defines both a set of variants, as well as which values distinguish amongst those variants). When used with [[ProductGroup]], this property can apply to any [[Product]] included in the group.

inputs.name: hasEnergyConsumptionDetails
inputs.help: Defines the energy efficiency Category (also known as "class" or "rating") for a product according to an international energy efficiency standard

inputs.name: audience
inputs.help: An intended audience, i.e. a group for whom something was created.

inputs.name: depth
inputs.help: The depth of the item.

inputs.name: height
inputs.help: The height of the item.

inputs.name: isRelatedTo
inputs.help: A pointer to another, somehow related product (or multiple products).

inputs.name: award
inputs.help: An award won by or for this item.

inputs.name: size
inputs.help: A standardized size of a product or creative work, often simplifying richer information into a simple textual string, either through referring to named sizes or (in the case of product markup), by adopting conventional simplifications. Use of QuantitativeValue with a unitCode or unitText can add more structure; in other cases, the /width, /height, /depth and /weight properties may be more applicable.

inputs.name: width
inputs.help: The width of the item.

inputs.name: pattern
inputs.help: A pattern that something has, for example 'polka dot', 'striped', 'Canadian flag'. Values are typically expressed as text, although links to controlled value schemes are also supported.

inputs.name: hasMerchantReturnPolicy
inputs.help: Indicates a MerchantReturnPolicy that may be applicable.

inputs.name: offers
inputs.help: An offer to provide this item—for example, an offer to sell a product, rent the DVD of a movie, perform a service, or give away tickets to an event. Use [[businessFunction]] to indicate the kind of transaction offered, i.e. sell, lease, etc. This property can also be used to describe a [[Demand]]. While this property is listed as expected on a number of common types, it can be used in others. In that case, using a second type, such as Product or a subtype of Product, can clarify the nature of the offer.

inputs.name: isConsumableFor
inputs.help: A pointer to another product (or multiple products) for which this product is a consumable.

inputs.name: productID
inputs.help: The product identifier, such as ISBN. For example: ``` meta itemprop="productID" content="isbn:123-456-789" ```.

inputs.name: aggregateRating
inputs.help: The overall rating, based on a collection of reviews or ratings, of the item.

inputs.name: gtin8
inputs.help: The [GTIN-8](http://apps.gs1.org/GDD/glossary/Pages/GTIN-8.aspx) code of the product, or the product to which the offer refers. This code is also known as EAN/UCC-8 or 8-digit EAN. See [GS1 GTIN Summary](http://www.gs1.org/barcodes/technical/idkeys/gtin) for more details.

inputs.name: nsn
inputs.help: Indicates the [NATO stock number](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/NATO_Stock_Number) (nsn) of a [[Product]].

inputs.name: isSimilarTo
inputs.help: A pointer to another, functionally similar product (or multiple products).

inputs.name: logo
inputs.help: An associated logo.

inputs.name: releaseDate
inputs.help: The release date of a product or product model. This can be used to distinguish the exact variant of a product.

inputs.name: mpn
inputs.help: The Manufacturer Part Number (MPN) of the product, or the product to which the offer refers.

inputs.name: purchaseDate
inputs.help: The date the item e.g. vehicle was purchased by the current owner.

inputs.name: gtin12
inputs.help: The GTIN-12 code of the product, or the product to which the offer refers. The GTIN-12 is the 12-digit GS1 Identification Key composed of a U.P.C. Company Prefix, Item Reference, and Check Digit used to identify trade items. See [GS1 GTIN Summary](http://www.gs1.org/barcodes/technical/idkeys/gtin) for more details.

inputs.name: category
inputs.help: A category for the item. Greater signs or slashes can be used to informally indicate a category hierarchy.

inputs.name: color
inputs.help: The color of the product.

inputs.name: inProductGroupWithID
inputs.help: Indicates the [[productGroupID]] for a [[ProductGroup]] that this product [[isVariantOf]].

inputs.name: sku
inputs.help: The Stock Keeping Unit (SKU), i.e. a merchant-specific identifier for a product or service, or the product to which the offer refers.

metadata.help: A DeliveryTimeSettings represents re-usable pieces of shipping information, relating to timing. It is designed for publication on an URL that may be referenced via the [[shippingSettingsLink]] property of a [[OfferShippingDetails]]. Several occurrences can be published, distinguished (and identified/referenced) by their different values for [[transitTimeLabel]].
metadata.name: DeliveryTimeSettings

inputs.name: transitTimeLabel
inputs.help: Label to match an [[OfferShippingDetails]] with a [[DeliveryTimeSettings]] (within the context of a [[shippingSettingsLink]] cross-reference).

inputs.name: deliveryTime
inputs.help: The total delay between the receipt of the order and the goods reaching the final customer.

inputs.name: shippingDestination
inputs.help: indicates (possibly multiple) shipping destinations. These can be defined in several ways e.g. postalCode ranges.

inputs.name: isUnlabelledFallback
inputs.help: This can be marked 'true' to indicate that some published [[DeliveryTimeSettings]] or [[ShippingRateSettings]] are intended to apply to all [[OfferShippingDetails]] published by the same merchant, when referenced by a [[shippingSettingsLink]] in those settings. It is not meaningful to use a 'true' value for this property alongside a transitTimeLabel (for [[DeliveryTimeSettings]]) or shippingLabel (for [[ShippingRateSettings]]), since this property is for use with unlabelled settings.

inputs.name: provider
inputs.help: The service provider, service operator, or service performer; the goods producer. Another party (a seller) may offer those services or goods on behalf of the provider. A provider may also serve as the seller.

inputs.name: partOfTrip
inputs.help: Identifies that this [[Trip]] is a subTrip of another Trip.  For example Day 1, Day 2, etc. of a multi-day trip.

inputs.name: offers
inputs.help: An offer to provide this item—for example, an offer to sell a product, rent the DVD of a movie, perform a service, or give away tickets to an event. Use [[businessFunction]] to indicate the kind of transaction offered, i.e. sell, lease, etc. This property can also be used to describe a [[Demand]]. While this property is listed as expected on a number of common types, it can be used in others. In that case, using a second type, such as Product or a subtype of Product, can clarify the nature of the offer.

inputs.name: departureTime
inputs.help: The expected departure time.

inputs.name: arrivalTime
inputs.help: The expected arrival time.

inputs.name: itinerary
inputs.help: Destination(s) ( [[Place]] ) that make up a trip. For a trip where destination order is important use [[ItemList]] to specify that order (see examples).

inputs.name: subTrip
inputs.help: Identifies a [[Trip]] that is a subTrip of this Trip.  For example Day 1, Day 2, etc. of a multi-day trip.

metadata.help: The geographic shape of a place. A GeoShape can be described using several properties whose values are based on latitude/longitude pairs. Either whitespace or commas can be used to separate latitude and longitude; whitespace should be used when writing a list of several such points.
metadata.name: GeoShape

inputs.name: address
inputs.help: Physical address of the item.

inputs.name: circle
inputs.help: A circle is the circular region of a specified radius centered at a specified latitude and longitude. A circle is expressed as a pair followed by a radius in meters.

inputs.name: addressCountry
inputs.help: The country. For example, USA. You can also provide the two-letter [ISO 3166-1 alpha-2 country code](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_3166-1).

inputs.name: polygon
inputs.help: A polygon is the area enclosed by a point-to-point path for which the starting and ending points are the same. A polygon is expressed as a series of four or more space delimited points where the first and final points are identical.

inputs.name: box
inputs.help: A box is the area enclosed by the rectangle formed by two points. The first point is the lower corner, the second point is the upper corner. A box is expressed as two points separated by a space character.

inputs.name: postalCode
inputs.help: The postal code. For example, 94043.

inputs.name: elevation
inputs.help: The elevation of a location ([WGS 84](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/World_Geodetic_System)). Values may be of the form 'NUMBER UNIT_OF_MEASUREMENT' (e.g., '1,000 m', '3,200 ft') while numbers alone should be assumed to be a value in meters.

inputs.name: line
inputs.help: A line is a point-to-point path consisting of two or more points. A line is expressed as a series of two or more point objects separated by space.

metadata.name: PropertyValueSpecification

inputs.help: Specifies the minimum allowed range for number of characters in a literal value.

inputs.name: readonlyValue
inputs.help: Whether or not a property is mutable.  Default is false. Specifying this for a property that also has a value makes it act similar to a "hidden" input in an HTML form.

inputs.name: valuePattern
inputs.help: Specifies a regular expression for testing literal values according to the HTML spec.

inputs.name: valueRequired
inputs.help: Whether the property must be filled in to complete the action.  Default is false.

inputs.name: valueMaxLength
inputs.help: Specifies the allowed range for number of characters in a literal value.

inputs.name: valueName
inputs.help: Indicates the name of the PropertyValueSpecification to be used in URL templates and form encoding in a manner analogous to HTML's input@name.

inputs.name: multipleValues
inputs.help: Whether multiple values are allowed for the property.  Default is false.

inputs.name: defaultValue
inputs.help: The default value of the input.  For properties that expect a literal, the default is a literal value, for properties that expect an object, it's an ID reference to one of the current values.

inputs.name: maxValue
inputs.help: The upper value of some characteristic or property.

inputs.name: minValue
inputs.help: The lower value of some characteristic or property.

inputs.name: stepValue
inputs.help: The stepValue attribute indicates the granularity that is expected (and required) of the value in a PropertyValueSpecification.

inputs.name: preOp
inputs.help: A description of the workup, testing, and other preparations required before implanting this device.

inputs.name: postOp
inputs.help: A description of the postoperative procedures, care, and/or followups for this device.

inputs.name: contraindication
inputs.help: A contraindication for this therapy.

inputs.name: adverseOutcome
inputs.help: A possible complication and/or side effect of this therapy. If it is known that an adverse outcome is serious (resulting in death, disability, or permanent damage; requiring hospitalization; or is otherwise life-threatening or requires immediate medical attention), tag it as a seriouseAdverseOutcome instead.

inputs.name: procedure
inputs.help: A description of the procedure involved in setting up, using, and/or installing the device.

inputs.name: seriousAdverseOutcome
inputs.help: A possible serious complication and/or serious side effect of this therapy. Serious adverse outcomes include those that are life-threatening; result in death, disability, or permanent damage; require hospitalization or prolong existing hospitalization; cause congenital anomalies or birth defects; or jeopardize the patient and may require medical or surgical intervention to prevent one of the outcomes in this definition.

metadata.help:
The act of transferring ownership of an object to a destination. Reciprocal of TakeAction.

Related actions:

* [[TakeAction]]: Reciprocal of GiveAction.
* [[SendAction]]: Unlike SendAction, GiveAction implies that ownership is being transferred (e.g. I may send my laptop to you, but that doesn't mean I'm giving it to you).
metadata.name: GiveAction

inputs.name: recipient
inputs.help: A sub property of participant. The participant who is at the receiving end of the action.

metadata.help: A datasheet or vendor specification of a product (in the sense of a prototypical description).

inputs.name: successorOf
inputs.help: A pointer from a newer variant of a product  to its previous, often discontinued predecessor.

inputs.name: predecessorOf
inputs.help: A pointer from a previous, often discontinued variant of the product to its newer variant.

inputs.name: isVariantOf
inputs.help: Indicates the kind of product that this is a variant of. In the case of [[ProductModel]], this is a pointer (from a ProductModel) to a base product from which this product is a variant. It is safe to infer that the variant inherits all product features from the base model, unless defined locally. This is not transitive. In the case of a [[ProductGroup]], the group description also serves as a template, representing a set of Products that vary on explicitly defined, specific dimensions only (so it defines both a set of variants, as well as which values distinguish amongst those variants). When used with [[ProductGroup]], this property can apply to any [[Product]] included in the group.

metadata.help: ShippingDeliveryTime provides various pieces of information about delivery times for shipping.
metadata.name: ShippingDeliveryTime

inputs.name: transitTime
inputs.help: The typical delay the order has been sent for delivery and the goods reach the final customer. Typical properties: minValue, maxValue, unitCode (d for DAY).

inputs.name: handlingTime
inputs.help: The typical delay between the receipt of the order and the goods either leaving the warehouse or being prepared for pickup, in case the delivery method is on site pickup. Typical properties: minValue, maxValue, unitCode (d for DAY).  This is by common convention assumed to mean business days (if a unitCode is used, coded as "d"), i.e. only counting days when the business normally operates.

inputs.name: businessDays
inputs.help: Days of the week when the merchant typically operates, indicated via opening hours markup.

inputs.name: cutoffTime
inputs.help: Order cutoff time allows merchants to describe the time after which they will no longer process orders received on that day. For orders processed after cutoff time, one day gets added to the delivery time estimate. This property is expected to be most typically used via the [[ShippingRateSettings]] publication pattern. The time is indicated using the ISO-8601 Time format, e.g. "23:30:00-05:00" would represent 6:30 pm Eastern Standard Time (EST) which is 5 hours behind Coordinated Universal Time (UTC).

metadata.help: A reservation to dine at a food-related business.\n\nNote: This type is for information about actual reservations, e.g. in confirmation emails or HTML pages with individual confirmations of reservations.
metadata.name: FoodEstablishmentReservation

inputs.name: partySize
inputs.help: Number of people the reservation should accommodate.

inputs.name: endTime
inputs.help: The endTime of something. For a reserved event or service (e.g. FoodEstablishmentReservation), the time that it is expected to end. For actions that span a period of time, when the action was performed. e.g. John wrote a book from January to *December*. For media, including audio and video, it's the time offset of the end of a clip within a larger file.\n\nNote that Event uses startDate/endDate instead of startTime/endTime, even when describing dates with times. This situation may be clarified in future revisions.

inputs.name: startTime
inputs.help: The startTime of something. For a reserved event or service (e.g. FoodEstablishmentReservation), the time that it is expected to start. For actions that span a period of time, when the action was performed. e.g. John wrote a book from *January* to December. For media, including audio and video, it's the time offset of the start of a clip within a larger file.\n\nNote that Event uses startDate/endDate instead of startTime/endTime, even when describing dates with times. This situation may be clarified in future revisions.

metadata.help: A list of possible conditions for the item.
metadata.name: OfferItemCondition

metadata.help: An indication for preventing an underlying condition, symptom, etc.
metadata.name: PreventionIndication

metadata.help: Enumerated status values for Order.
metadata.name: OrderStatus

metadata.help: A demand entity represents the public, not necessarily binding, not necessarily exclusive, announcement by an organization or person to seek a certain type of goods or services. For describing demand using this type, the very same properties used for Offer apply.
metadata.name: Demand

inputs.name: gtin13
inputs.help: The GTIN-13 code of the product, or the product to which the offer refers. This is equivalent to 13-digit ISBN codes and EAN UCC-13. Former 12-digit UPC codes can be converted into a GTIN-13 code by simply adding a preceding zero. See [GS1 GTIN Summary](http://www.gs1.org/barcodes/technical/idkeys/gtin) for more details.

inputs.name: itemOffered
inputs.help: An item being offered (or demanded). The transactional nature of the offer or demand is documented using [[businessFunction]], e.g. sell, lease etc. While several common expected types are listed explicitly in this definition, others can be used. Using a second type, such as Product or a subtype of Product, can clarify the nature of the offer.

inputs.name: deliveryLeadTime
inputs.help: The typical delay between the receipt of the order and the goods either leaving the warehouse or being prepared for pickup, in case the delivery method is on site pickup.

inputs.name: eligibleQuantity
inputs.help: The interval and unit of measurement of ordering quantities for which the offer or price specification is valid. This allows e.g. specifying that a certain freight charge is valid only for a certain quantity.

inputs.name: availability
inputs.help: The availability of this item—for example In stock, Out of stock, Pre-order, etc.

inputs.name: serialNumber
inputs.help: The serial number or any alphanumeric identifier of a particular product. When attached to an offer, it is a shortcut for the serial number of the product included in the offer.

inputs.name: gtin
inputs.help: A Global Trade Item Number ([GTIN](https://www.gs1.org/standards/id-keys/gtin)). GTINs identify trade items, including products and services, using numeric identification codes. The [[gtin]] property generalizes the earlier [[gtin8]], [[gtin12]], [[gtin13]], and [[gtin14]] properties. The GS1 [digital link specifications](https://www.gs1.org/standards/Digital-Link/) express GTINs as URLs. A correct [[gtin]] value should be a valid GTIN, which means that it should be an all-numeric string of either 8, 12, 13 or 14 digits, or a "GS1 Digital Link" URL based on such a string. The numeric component should also have a [valid GS1 check digit](https://www.gs1.org/services/check-digit-calculator) and meet the other rules for valid GTINs. See also [GS1's GTIN Summary](http://www.gs1.org/barcodes/technical/idkeys/gtin) and [Wikipedia](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Global_Trade_Item_Number) for more details. Left-padding of the gtin values is not required or encouraged.

inputs.name: itemCondition
inputs.help: A predefined value from OfferItemCondition or a textual description of the condition of the product or service, or the products or services included in the offer.

inputs.name: gtin14
inputs.help: The GTIN-14 code of the product, or the product to which the offer refers. See [GS1 GTIN Summary](http://www.gs1.org/barcodes/technical/idkeys/gtin) for more details.

inputs.name: includesObject
inputs.help: This links to a node or nodes indicating the exact quantity of the products included in  an [[Offer]] or [[ProductCollection]].

inputs.name: advanceBookingRequirement
inputs.help: The amount of time that is required between accepting the offer and the actual usage of the resource or service.

inputs.name: availableAtOrFrom
inputs.help: The place(s) from which the offer can be obtained (e.g. store locations).

inputs.name: ineligibleRegion
inputs.help: The ISO 3166-1 (ISO 3166-1 alpha-2) or ISO 3166-2 code, the place, or the GeoShape for the geo-political region(s) for which the offer or delivery charge specification is not valid, e.g. a region where the transaction is not allowed.\n\nSee also [[eligibleRegion]].

inputs.name: eligibleDuration
inputs.help: The duration for which the given offer is valid.

inputs.name: businessFunction
inputs.help: The business function (e.g. sell, lease, repair, dispose) of the offer or component of a bundle (TypeAndQuantityNode). The default is http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#Sell.

inputs.name: priceSpecification
inputs.help: One or more detailed price specifications, indicating the unit price and delivery or payment charges.

inputs.name: warranty
inputs.help: The warranty promise(s) included in the offer.

inputs.name: eligibleTransactionVolume
inputs.help: The transaction volume, in a monetary unit, for which the offer or price specification is valid, e.g. for indicating a minimal purchasing volume, to express free shipping above a certain order volume, or to limit the acceptance of credit cards to purchases to a certain minimal amount.

inputs.name: validThrough
inputs.help: The date after when the item is not valid. For example the end of an offer, salary period, or a period of opening hours.

inputs.name: gtin8
inputs.help: The [GTIN-8](http://apps.gs1.org/GDD/glossary/Pages/GTIN-8.aspx) code of the product, or the product to which the offer refers. This code is also known as EAN/UCC-8 or 8-digit EAN. See [GS1 GTIN Summary](http://www.gs1.org/barcodes/technical/idkeys/gtin) for more details.

inputs.name: availabilityEnds
inputs.help: The end of the availability of the product or service included in the offer.

inputs.name: eligibleCustomerType
inputs.help: The type(s) of customers for which the given offer is valid.

inputs.name: inventoryLevel
inputs.help: The current approximate inventory level for the item or items.

inputs.name: availableDeliveryMethod
inputs.help: The delivery method(s) available for this offer.

inputs.name: seller
inputs.help: An entity which offers (sells / leases / lends / loans) the services / goods.  A seller may also be a provider.

inputs.name: mpn
inputs.help: The Manufacturer Part Number (MPN) of the product, or the product to which the offer refers.

inputs.name: eligibleRegion
inputs.help: The ISO 3166-1 (ISO 3166-1 alpha-2) or ISO 3166-2 code, the place, or the GeoShape for the geo-political region(s) for which the offer or delivery charge specification is valid.\n\nSee also [[ineligibleRegion]].

inputs.name: availabilityStarts
inputs.help: The beginning of the availability of the product or service included in the offer.

inputs.name: validFrom
inputs.help: The date when the item becomes valid.

inputs.name: gtin12
inputs.help: The GTIN-12 code of the product, or the product to which the offer refers. The GTIN-12 is the 12-digit GS1 Identification Key composed of a U.P.C. Company Prefix, Item Reference, and Check Digit used to identify trade items. See [GS1 GTIN Summary](http://www.gs1.org/barcodes/technical/idkeys/gtin) for more details.

inputs.name: areaServed
inputs.help: The geographic area where a service or offered item is provided.

inputs.name: acceptedPaymentMethod
inputs.help: The payment method(s) accepted by seller for this offer.

inputs.name: sku
inputs.help: The Stock Keeping Unit (SKU), i.e. a merchant-specific identifier for a product or service, or the product to which the offer refers.

inputs.name: valueReference
inputs.help: A pointer to a secondary value that provides additional information on the original value, e.g. a reference temperature.

inputs.name: additionalProperty

inputs.name: lesserOrEqual

inputs.name: greaterOrEqual

inputs.name: lesser

inputs.name: nonEqual

inputs.name: equal

inputs.name: occupancy
inputs.help:
The allowed total occupancy for the accommodation in persons (including infants etc). For individual accommodations, this is not necessarily the legal maximum but defines the permitted usage as per the contractual agreement (e.g. a double room used by a single person).
Typical unit code(s): C62 for person

inputs.name: numberOfRooms
inputs.help:
The number of rooms (excluding bathrooms and closets) of the accommodation or lodging business.
Typical unit code(s): ROM for room or C62 for no unit. The type of room can be put in the unitText property of the QuantitativeValue.

metadata.help:
A delivery method is a standardized procedure for transferring the product or service to the destination of fulfillment chosen by the customer. Delivery methods are characterized by the means of transportation used, and by the organization or group that is the contracting party for the sending organization or person.

Commonly used values:

* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#DeliveryModeDirectDownload
* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#DeliveryModeFreight
* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#DeliveryModeMail
* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#DeliveryModeOwnFleet
* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#DeliveryModePickUp
* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#DHL
* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#FederalExpress
* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#UPS

inputs.name: availableFrom
inputs.help: When the item is available for pickup from the store, locker, etc.

metadata.help: A chemical or biologic substance, used as a medical therapy, that has a physiological effect on an organism. Here the term drug is used interchangeably with the term medicine although clinical knowledge make a clear difference between them.
metadata.name: Drug

inputs.name: warning
inputs.help: Any FDA or other warnings about the drug (text or URL).

inputs.name: clincalPharmacology
inputs.help: Description of the absorption and elimination of drugs, including their concentration (pharmacokinetics, pK) and biological effects (pharmacodynamics, pD).

inputs.name: activeIngredient
inputs.help: An active ingredient, typically chemical compounds and/or biologic substances.

inputs.name: manufacturer
inputs.help: The manufacturer of the product.

inputs.name: maximumIntake
inputs.help: Recommended intake of this supplement for a given population as defined by a specific recommending authority.

inputs.name: doseSchedule
inputs.help: A dosing schedule for the drug for a given population, either observed, recommended, or maximum dose based on the type used.

inputs.name: breastfeedingWarning
inputs.help: Any precaution, guidance, contraindication, etc. related to this drug's use by breastfeeding mothers.

inputs.name: nonProprietaryName
inputs.help: The generic name of this drug or supplement.

inputs.name: mechanismOfAction
inputs.help: The specific biochemical interaction through which this drug or supplement produces its pharmacological effect.

inputs.name: dosageForm
inputs.help: A dosage form in which this drug/supplement is available, e.g. 'tablet', 'suspension', 'injection'.

inputs.name: pregnancyCategory
inputs.help: Pregnancy category of this drug.

inputs.name: foodWarning
inputs.help: Any precaution, guidance, contraindication, etc. related to consumption of specific foods while taking this drug.

inputs.name: relatedDrug
inputs.help: Any other drug related to this one, for example commonly-prescribed alternatives.

inputs.name: pregnancyWarning
inputs.help: Any precaution, guidance, contraindication, etc. related to this drug's use during pregnancy.

inputs.name: drugUnit
inputs.help: The unit in which the drug is measured, e.g. '5 mg tablet'.

inputs.name: drugClass
inputs.help: The class of drug this belongs to (e.g., statins).

inputs.name: prescribingInfo
inputs.help: Link to prescribing information for the drug.

inputs.name: interactingDrug
inputs.help: Another drug that is known to interact with this drug in a way that impacts the effect of this drug or causes a risk to the patient. Note: disease interactions are typically captured as contraindications.

inputs.name: proprietaryName
inputs.help: Proprietary name given to the diet plan, typically by its originator or creator.

inputs.name: prescriptionStatus
inputs.help: Indicates the status of drug prescription eg. local catalogs classifications or whether the drug is available by prescription or over-the-counter, etc.

inputs.name: administrationRoute
inputs.help: A route by which this drug may be administered, e.g. 'oral'.

inputs.name: legalStatus
inputs.help: The drug or supplement's legal status, including any controlled substance schedules that apply.

inputs.name: availableStrength
inputs.help: An available dosage strength for the drug.

inputs.name: labelDetails
inputs.help: Link to the drug's label details.

inputs.name: isAvailableGenerically
inputs.help: True if the drug is available in a generic form (regardless of name).

inputs.name: alcoholWarning
inputs.help: Any precaution, guidance, contraindication, etc. related to consumption of alcohol while taking this drug.

inputs.name: overdosage
inputs.help: Any information related to overdose on a drug, including signs or symptoms, treatments, contact information for emergency response.

inputs.name: rxcui
inputs.help: The RxCUI drug identifier from RXNORM.

inputs.name: isProprietary
inputs.help: True if this item's name is a proprietary/brand name (vs. generic name).

inputs.name: includedInHealthInsurancePlan
inputs.help: The insurance plans that cover this drug.

inputs.name: clinicalPharmacology
inputs.help: Description of the absorption and elimination of drugs, including their concentration (pharmacokinetics, pK) and biological effects (pharmacodynamics, pD).

metadata.help: A software application.
metadata.name: SoftwareApplication

inputs.name: requirements
inputs.help: Component dependency requirements for application. This includes runtime environments and shared libraries that are not included in the application distribution package, but required to run the application (Examples: DirectX, Java or .NET runtime).

inputs.name: softwareHelp
inputs.help: Software application help.

inputs.name: supportingData
inputs.help: Supporting data for a SoftwareApplication.

inputs.name: fileSize
inputs.help: Size of the application / package (e.g. 18MB). In the absence of a unit (MB, KB etc.), KB will be assumed.

inputs.name: screenshot
inputs.help: A link to a screenshot image of the app.

inputs.name: softwareVersion
inputs.help: Version of the software instance.

inputs.name: applicationSuite
inputs.help: The name of the application suite to which the application belongs (e.g. Excel belongs to Office).

inputs.name: softwareAddOn
inputs.help: Additional content for a software application.

inputs.name: availableOnDevice
inputs.help: Device required to run the application. Used in cases where a specific make/model is required to run the application.

inputs.name: applicationCategory
inputs.help: Type of software application, e.g. 'Game, Multimedia'.

inputs.name: countriesNotSupported
inputs.help: Countries for which the application is not supported. You can also provide the two-letter ISO 3166-1 alpha-2 country code.

inputs.name: device
inputs.help: Device required to run the application. Used in cases where a specific make/model is required to run the application.

inputs.name: storageRequirements
inputs.help: Storage requirements (free space required).

inputs.name: processorRequirements
inputs.help: Processor architecture required to run the application (e.g. IA64).

inputs.name: featureList
inputs.help: Features or modules provided by this application (and possibly required by other applications).

inputs.name: countriesSupported
inputs.help: Countries for which the application is supported. You can also provide the two-letter ISO 3166-1 alpha-2 country code.

inputs.name: softwareRequirements
inputs.help: Component dependency requirements for application. This includes runtime environments and shared libraries that are not included in the application distribution package, but required to run the application (Examples: DirectX, Java or .NET runtime).

inputs.name: operatingSystem
inputs.help: Operating systems supported (Windows 7, OSX 10.6, Android 1.6).

inputs.name: applicationSubCategory
inputs.help: Subcategory of the application, e.g. 'Arcade Game'.

inputs.name: releaseNotes
inputs.help: Description of what changed in this version.

inputs.name: permissions
inputs.help: Permission(s) required to run the app (for example, a mobile app may require full internet access or may run only on wifi).

inputs.name: installUrl
inputs.help: URL at which the app may be installed, if different from the URL of the item.

inputs.name: downloadUrl
inputs.help: If the file can be downloaded, URL to download the binary.

inputs.name: memoryRequirements
inputs.help: Minimum memory requirements.

inputs.name: nerveMotor

inputs.name: petsAllowed

inputs.name: checkinTime

inputs.name: availableLanguage
inputs.help: A language someone may use with or at the item, service or place. Please use one of the language codes from the [IETF BCP 47 standard](http://tools.ietf.org/html/bcp47). See also [[inLanguage]]

inputs.name: audience
inputs.help: An intended audience, i.e. a group for whom something was created.

inputs.name: starRating

inputs.name: amenityFeature
inputs.help: An amenity feature (e.g. a characteristic or service) of the Accommodation. This generic property does not make a statement about whether the feature is included in an offer for the main accommodation or available at extra costs.

inputs.name: numberOfRooms
inputs.help:
The number of rooms (excluding bathrooms and closets) of the accommodation or lodging business.
Typical unit code(s): ROM for room or C62 for no unit. The type of room can be put in the unitText property of the QuantitativeValue.

metadata.name: TradeAction

inputs.name: price
inputs.help:
The offer price of a product, or of a price component when attached to PriceSpecification and its subtypes.

Usage guidelines:

* Use the [[priceCurrency]] property (with standard formats: [ISO 4217 currency format](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_4217) e.g. "USD"; [Ticker symbol](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_cryptocurrencies) for cryptocurrencies e.g. "BTC"; well known names for [Local Exchange Tradings Systems](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Local_exchange_trading_system) (LETS) and other currency types e.g. "Ithaca HOUR") instead of including [ambiguous symbols](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dollar_sign#Currencies_that_use_the_dollar_or_peso_sign) such as '$' in the value.
* Use '.' (Unicode 'FULL STOP' (U+002E)) rather than ',' to indicate a decimal point. Avoid using these symbols as a readability separator.
* Note that both [RDFa](http://www.w3.org/TR/xhtml-rdfa-primer/#using-the-content-attribute) and Microdata syntax allow the use of a "content=" attribute for publishing simple machine-readable values alongside more human-friendly formatting.
* Use values from 0123456789 (Unicode 'DIGIT ZERO' (U+0030) to 'DIGIT NINE' (U+0039)) rather than superficially similiar Unicode symbols.

inputs.name: priceCurrency
inputs.help: The currency of the price, or a price component when attached to [[PriceSpecification]] and its subtypes.\n\nUse standard formats: [ISO 4217 currency format](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_4217) e.g. "USD"; [Ticker symbol](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_cryptocurrencies) for cryptocurrencies e.g. "BTC"; well known names for [Local Exchange Tradings Systems](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Local_exchange_trading_system) (LETS) and other currency types e.g. "Ithaca HOUR".

inputs.name: priceSpecification
inputs.help: One or more detailed price specifications, indicating the unit price and delivery or payment charges.

metadata.help: A program offered by an institution which determines the learning progress to achieve an outcome, usually a credential like a degree or certificate. This would define a discrete set of opportunities (e.g., job, courses) that together constitute a program with a clear start, end, set of requirements, and transition to a new occupational opportunity (e.g., a job), or sometimes a higher educational opportunity (e.g., an advanced degree).
metadata.name: EducationalOccupationalProgram

inputs.name: hasCourse
inputs.help: A course or class that is one of the learning opportunities that constitute an educational / occupational program. No information is implied about whether the course is mandatory or optional; no guarantee is implied about whether the course will be available to everyone on the program.

inputs.name: applicationStartDate
inputs.help: The date at which the program begins collecting applications for the next enrollment cycle.

inputs.name: timeOfDay
inputs.help: The time of day the program normally runs. For example, "evenings".

inputs.name: maximumEnrollment
inputs.help: The maximum number of students who may be enrolled in the program.

inputs.name: endDate
inputs.help: The end date and time of the item (in [ISO 8601 date format](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_8601)).

inputs.name: financialAidEligible
inputs.help: A financial aid type or program which students may use to pay for tuition or fees associated with the program.

inputs.name: programPrerequisites
inputs.help: Prerequisites for enrolling in the program.

inputs.name: provider
inputs.help: The service provider, service operator, or service performer; the goods producer. Another party (a seller) may offer those services or goods on behalf of the provider. A provider may also serve as the seller.

inputs.name: typicalCreditsPerTerm
inputs.help: The number of credits or units a full-time student would be expected to take in 1 term however 'term' is defined by the institution.

inputs.name: occupationalCategory
inputs.help:
A category describing the job, preferably using a term from a taxonomy such as [BLS O*NET-SOC](http://www.onetcenter.org/taxonomy.html), [ISCO-08](https://www.ilo.org/public/english/bureau/stat/isco/isco08/) or similar, with the property repeated for each applicable value. Ideally the taxonomy should be identified, and both the textual label and formal code for the category should be provided.\n
Note: for historical reasons, any textual label and formal code provided as a literal may be assumed to be from O*NET-SOC.

inputs.name: occupationalCredentialAwarded
inputs.help: A description of the qualification, award, certificate, diploma or other occupational credential awarded as a consequence of successful completion of this course or program.

inputs.name: termsPerYear
inputs.help: The number of times terms of study are offered per year. Semesters and quarters are common units for term. For example, if the student can only take 2 semesters for the program in one year, then termsPerYear should be 2.

inputs.name: programType
inputs.help: The type of educational or occupational program. For example, classroom, internship, alternance, etc..

inputs.name: timeToComplete
inputs.help: The expected length of time to complete the program if attending full-time.

inputs.name: offers
inputs.help: An offer to provide this item—for example, an offer to sell a product, rent the DVD of a movie, perform a service, or give away tickets to an event. Use [[businessFunction]] to indicate the kind of transaction offered, i.e. sell, lease, etc. This property can also be used to describe a [[Demand]]. While this property is listed as expected on a number of common types, it can be used in others. In that case, using a second type, such as Product or a subtype of Product, can clarify the nature of the offer.

inputs.name: dayOfWeek
inputs.help: The day of the week for which these opening hours are valid.

inputs.name: termDuration
inputs.help: The amount of time in a term as defined by the institution. A term is a length of time where students take one or more classes. Semesters and quarters are common units for term.

inputs.name: applicationDeadline
inputs.help: The date at which the program stops collecting applications for the next enrollment cycle.

inputs.name: educationalCredentialAwarded
inputs.help: A description of the qualification, award, certificate, diploma or other educational credential awarded as a consequence of successful completion of this course or program.

inputs.name: trainingSalary
inputs.help: The estimated salary earned while in the program.

inputs.name: educationalProgramMode
inputs.help: Similar to courseMode, The medium or means of delivery of the program as a whole. The value may either be a text label (e.g. "online", "onsite" or "blended"; "synchronous" or "asynchronous"; "full-time" or "part-time") or a URL reference to a term from a controlled vocabulary (e.g. https://ceds.ed.gov/element/001311#Asynchronous ).

inputs.name: numberOfCredits
inputs.help: The number of credits or units awarded by a Course or required to complete an EducationalOccupationalProgram.

inputs.name: salaryUponCompletion
inputs.help: The expected salary upon completing the training.

inputs.name: startDate
inputs.help: The start date and time of the item (in [ISO 8601 date format](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_8601)).

metadata.help:
A StatisticalPopulation is a set of instances of a certain given type that satisfy some set of constraints. The property [[populationType]] is used to specify the type. Any property that can be used on instances of that type can appear on the statistical population. For example, a [[StatisticalPopulation]] representing all [[Person]]s with a [[homeLocation]] of East Podunk California, would be described by applying the appropriate [[homeLocation]] and [[populationType]] properties to a [[StatisticalPopulation]] item that stands for that set of people.
The properties [[numConstraints]] and [[constrainingProperties]] are used to specify which of the populations properties are used to specify the population. Note that the sense of "population" used here is the general sense of a statistical
population, and does not imply that the population consists of people. For example, a [[populationType]] of [[Event]] or [[NewsArticle]] could be used. See also [[Observation]], and the [data and datasets](/docs/data-and-datasets.html) overview for more details.
metadata.name: StatisticalPopulation

inputs.name: populationType
inputs.help: Indicates the populationType common to all members of a [[StatisticalPopulation]].

inputs.name: constrainingProperty
inputs.help:
Indicates a property used as a constraint to define a [[StatisticalPopulation]] with respect to the set of entities
  corresponding to an indicated type (via [[populationType]]).

inputs.name: numConstraints
inputs.help: Indicates the number of constraints (not counting [[populationType]]) defined for a particular [[StatisticalPopulation]]. This helps applications understand if they have access to a sufficiently complete description of a [[StatisticalPopulation]].

metadata.help:
A SpecialAnnouncement combines a simple date-stamped textual information update
      with contextualized Web links and other structured data.  It represents an information update made by a
      locally-oriented organization, for example schools, pharmacies, healthcare providers,  community groups, police,
      local government.

For work in progress guidelines on Coronavirus-related markup see [this doc](https://docs.google.com/document/d/14ikaGCKxo50rRM7nvKSlbUpjyIk2WMQd3IkB1lItlrM/edit#).

The motivating scenario for SpecialAnnouncement is the [Coronavirus pandemic](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2019%E2%80%9320_coronavirus_pandemic), and the initial vocabulary is oriented to this urgent situation. Schema.org
expect to improve the markup iteratively as it is deployed and as feedback emerges from use. In addition to our
usual [Github entry](https://github.com/schemaorg/schemaorg/issues/2490), feedback comments can also be provided in [this document](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1fpdFFxk8s87CWwACs53SGkYv3aafSxz_DTtOQxMrBJQ/edit#).


While this schema is designed to communicate urgent crisis-related information, it is not the same as an emergency warning technology like [CAP](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Common_Alerting_Protocol), although there may be overlaps. The intent is to cover
the kinds of everyday practical information being posted to existing websites during an emergency situation.

Several kinds of information can be provided:

We encourage the provision of "name", "text", "datePosted", "expires" (if appropriate), "category" and
"url" as a simple baseline. It is important to provide a value for "category" where possible, most ideally as a well known
URL from Wikipedia or Wikidata. In the case of the 2019-2020 Coronavirus pandemic, this should be "https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=2019-20\_coronavirus\_pandemic" or "https://www.wikidata.org/wiki/Q81068910".

For many of the possible properties, values can either be simple links or an inline description, depending on whether a summary is available. For a link, provide just the URL of the appropriate page as the property's value. For an inline description, use a [[WebContent]] type, and provide the url as a property of that, alongside at least a simple "[[text]]" summary of the page. It is
unlikely that a single SpecialAnnouncement will need all of the possible properties simultaneously.

We expect that in many cases the page referenced might contain more specialized structured data, e.g. contact info, [[openingHours]], [[Event]], [[FAQPage]] etc. By linking to those pages from a [[SpecialAnnouncement]] you can help make it clearer that the events are related to the situation (e.g. Coronavirus) indicated by the [[category]] property of the [[SpecialAnnouncement]].

Many [[SpecialAnnouncement]]s will relate to particular regions and to identifiable local organizations. Use [[spatialCoverage]] for the region, and [[announcementLocation]] to indicate specific [[LocalBusiness]]es and [[CivicStructures]]. If the announcement affects both a particular region and a specific location (for example, a library closure that serves an entire region), use both [[spatialCoverage]] and [[announcementLocation]].

The [[about]] property can be used to indicate entities that are the focus of the announcement. We now recommend using [[about]] only
for representing non-location entities (e.g. a [[Course]] or a [[RadioStation]]). For places, use [[announcementLocation]] and [[spatialCoverage]]. Consumers of this markup should be aware that the initial design encouraged the use of /about for locations too.

The basic content of [[SpecialAnnouncement]] is similar to that of an [RSS](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/RSS) or [Atom](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Atom_(Web_standard)) feed. For publishers without such feeds, basic feed-like information can be shared by posting
[[SpecialAnnouncement]] updates in a page, e.g. using JSON-LD. For sites with Atom/RSS functionality, you can point to a feed
with the [[webFeed]] property. This can be a simple URL, or an inline [[DataFeed]] object, with [[encodingFormat]] providing
media type information e.g. "application/rss+xml" or "application/atom+xml".
metadata.name: SpecialAnnouncement

inputs.name: governmentBenefitsInfo
inputs.help: governmentBenefitsInfo provides information about government benefits associated with a SpecialAnnouncement.

inputs.name: webFeed
inputs.help: The URL for a feed, e.g. associated with a podcast series, blog, or series of date-stamped updates. This is usually RSS or Atom.

inputs.name: diseaseSpreadStatistics
inputs.help:
Statistical information about the spread of a disease, either as [[WebContent]], or
  described directly as a [[Dataset]], or the specific [[Observation]]s in the dataset. When a [[WebContent]] URL is
  provided, the page indicated might also contain more such markup.

inputs.name: gettingTestedInfo
inputs.help: Information about getting tested (for a [[MedicalCondition]]), e.g. in the context of a pandemic.

inputs.name: travelBans
inputs.help: Information about travel bans, e.g. in the context of a pandemic.

inputs.name: newsUpdatesAndGuidelines
inputs.help: Indicates a page with news updates and guidelines. This could often be (but is not required to be) the main page containing [[SpecialAnnouncement]] markup on a site.

inputs.name: schoolClosuresInfo
inputs.help: Information about school closures.

inputs.name: quarantineGuidelines
inputs.help: Guidelines about quarantine rules, e.g. in the context of a pandemic.

inputs.name: diseasePreventionInfo
inputs.help: Information about disease prevention.

inputs.name: datePosted
inputs.help: Publication date of an online listing.

inputs.name: publicTransportClosuresInfo
inputs.help: Information about public transport closures.

inputs.name: announcementLocation
inputs.help: Indicates a specific [[CivicStructure]] or [[LocalBusiness]] associated with the SpecialAnnouncement. For example, a specific testing facility or business with special opening hours. For a larger geographic region like a quarantine of an entire region, use [[spatialCoverage]].

inputs.name: category
inputs.help: A category for the item. Greater signs or slashes can be used to informally indicate a category hierarchy.

metadata.help: A set of defined terms for example a set of categories or a classification scheme, a glossary, dictionary or enumeration.
metadata.name: DefinedTermSet

inputs.name: hasDefinedTerm
inputs.help: A Defined Term contained in this term set.

metadata.help: A MerchantReturnPolicy provides information about product return policies associated with an [[Organization]] or [[Product]].
metadata.name: MerchantReturnPolicy

inputs.name: refundType
inputs.help: A refundType, from an enumerated list.

inputs.name: merchantReturnDays
inputs.help: The merchantReturnDays property indicates the number of days (from purchase) within which relevant merchant return policy is applicable.

inputs.name: returnFees
inputs.help: Indicates (via enumerated options) the return fees policy for a MerchantReturnPolicy

inputs.name: inStoreReturnsOffered
inputs.help: Are in-store returns offered?

inputs.name: merchantReturnLink
inputs.help: Indicates a Web page or service by URL, for product return.

inputs.name: returnPolicyCategory
inputs.help: A returnPolicyCategory expresses at most one of several enumerated kinds of return.

metadata.help: A legal document such as an act, decree, bill, etc. (enforceable or not) or a component of a legal act (like an article).
metadata.name: Legislation

inputs.name: legislationApplies
inputs.help: Indicates that this legislation (or part of a legislation) somehow transfers another legislation in a different legislative context. This is an informative link, and it has no legal value. For legally-binding links of transposition, use the legislationTransposes property. For example an informative consolidated law of a European Union's member state "applies" the consolidated version of the European Directive implemented in it.

inputs.name: legislationType
inputs.help: The type of the legislation. Examples of values are "law", "act", "directive", "decree", "regulation", "statutory instrument", "loi organique", "rglement grand-ducal", etc., depending on the country.

inputs.name: legislationDate
inputs.help: The date of adoption or signature of the legislation. This is the date at which the text is officially aknowledged to be a legislation, even though it might not even be published or in force.

inputs.name: legislationResponsible
inputs.help: An individual or organization that has some kind of responsibility for the legislation. Typically the ministry who is/was in charge of elaborating the legislation, or the adressee for potential questions about the legislation once it is published.

inputs.name: legislationIdentifier
inputs.help: An identifier for the legislation. This can be either a string-based identifier, like the CELEX at EU level or the NOR in France, or a web-based, URL/URI identifier, like an ELI (European Legislation Identifier) or an URN-Lex.

inputs.name: legislationTransposes
inputs.help: Indicates that this legislation (or part of legislation) fulfills the objectives set by another legislation, by passing appropriate implementation measures. Typically, some legislations of European Union's member states or regions transpose European Directives. This indicates a legally binding link between the 2 legislations.

inputs.name: jurisdiction
inputs.help: Indicates a legal jurisdiction, e.g. of some legislation, or where some government service is based.

inputs.name: legislationChanges
inputs.help: Another legislation that this legislation changes. This encompasses the notions of amendment, replacement, correction, repeal, or other types of change. This may be a direct change (textual or non-textual amendment) or a consequential or indirect change. The property is to be used to express the existence of a change relationship between two acts rather than the existence of a consolidated version of the text that shows the result of the change. For consolidation relationships, use the legislationConsolidates property.

inputs.name: legislationDateVersion
inputs.help: The point-in-time at which the provided description of the legislation is valid (e.g. : when looking at the law on the 2016-04-07 (= dateVersion), I get the consolidation of 2015-04-12 of the "National Insurance Contributions Act 2015")

inputs.name: legislationConsolidates
inputs.help: Indicates another legislation taken into account in this consolidated legislation (which is usually the product of an editorial process that revises the legislation). This property should be used multiple times to refer to both the original version or the previous consolidated version, and to the legislations making the change.

inputs.name: legislationPassedBy
inputs.help: The person or organization that originally passed or made the law : typically parliament (for primary legislation) or government (for secondary legislation). This indicates the "legal author" of the law, as opposed to its physical author.

inputs.name: legislationLegalForce
inputs.help: Whether the legislation is currently in force, not in force, or partially in force.

inputs.name: legislationJurisdiction
inputs.help: The jurisdiction from which the legislation originates.

Country: US

Region = state, canton, prefecture, autonomous community...

metadata.help:
The act of forming a personal connection with someone/something (object) unidirectionally/asymmetrically to get updates polled from.

Related actions:

* [[BefriendAction]]: Unlike BefriendAction, FollowAction implies that the connection is *not* necessarily reciprocal.
* [[SubscribeAction]]: Unlike SubscribeAction, FollowAction implies that the follower acts as an active agent constantly/actively polling for updates.
* [[RegisterAction]]: Unlike RegisterAction, FollowAction implies that the agent is interested in continuing receiving updates from the object.
* [[JoinAction]]: Unlike JoinAction, FollowAction implies that the agent is interested in getting updates from the object.
* [[TrackAction]]: Unlike TrackAction, FollowAction refers to the polling of updates of all aspects of animate objects rather than the location of inanimate objects (e.g. you track a package, but you don't follow it).

inputs.name: measurementTechnique
inputs.help:
A technique or technology used in a [[Dataset]] (or [[DataDownload]], [[DataCatalog]]),
corresponding to the method used for measuring the corresponding variable(s) (described using [[variableMeasured]]). This is oriented towards scientific and scholarly dataset publication but may have broader applicability; it is not intended as a full representation of measurement, but rather as a high level summary for dataset discovery.

For example, if [[variableMeasured]] is: molecule concentration, [[measurementTechnique]] could be: "mass spectrometry" or "nmr spectroscopy" or "colorimetry" or "immunofluorescence".

If the [[variableMeasured]] is "depression rating", the [[measurementTechnique]] could be "Zung Scale" or "HAM-D" or "Beck Depression Inventory".

If there are several [[variableMeasured]] properties recorded for some given data object, use a [[PropertyValue]] for each [[variableMeasured]] and attach the corresponding [[measurementTechnique]].

inputs.name: loanType
inputs.help: The type of a loan or credit.

inputs.name: recourseLoan
inputs.help: The only way you get the money back in the event of default is the security. Recourse is where you still have the opportunity to go back to the borrower for the rest of the money.

inputs.name: amount
inputs.help: The amount of money.

inputs.name: requiredCollateral
inputs.help: Assets required to secure loan or credit repayments. It may take form of third party pledge, goods, financial instruments (cash, securities, etc.)

inputs.name: loanTerm
inputs.help: The duration of the loan or credit agreement.

inputs.name: gracePeriod
inputs.help: The period of time after any due date that the borrower has to fulfil its obligations before a default (failure to pay) is deemed to have occurred.

inputs.name: loanRepaymentForm
inputs.help: A form of paying back money previously borrowed from a lender. Repayment usually takes the form of periodic payments that normally include part principal plus interest in each payment.

inputs.name: renegotiableLoan
inputs.help: Whether the terms for payment of interest can be renegotiated during the life of the loan.

inputs.name: currency

inputs.name: partOfInvoice

inputs.name: paymentUrl

inputs.name: customer

inputs.name: discount

inputs.name: confirmationNumber

inputs.name: orderedItem

inputs.name: discountCurrency

inputs.help: The number of items in an ItemList. Note that some descriptions might not fully describe all items in a list (e.g., multi-page pagination); in such cases, the numberOfItems would be for the entire list.

inputs.name: itemListElement
inputs.help:
For itemListElement values, you can use simple strings (e.g. "Peter", "Paul", "Mary"), existing entities, or use ListItem.

Text values are best if the elements in the list are plain strings. Existing entities are best for a simple, unordered list of existing things in your data. ListItem is used with ordered lists when you want to provide additional context about the element in that list or when the same item might be in different places in different lists.

Note: The order of elements in your mark-up is not sufficient for indicating the order or elements.  Use ListItem with a 'position' property in such cases.

inputs.name: sameAs
inputs.help: URL of a reference Web page that unambiguously indicates the item's identity. E.g. the URL of the item's Wikipedia page, Wikidata entry, or official website.

inputs.name: mainEntityOfPage
inputs.help: Indicates a page (or other CreativeWork) for which this thing is the main entity being described. See [background notes](/docs/datamodel.html#mainEntityBackground) for details.

inputs.name: potentialAction
inputs.help: Indicates a potential Action, which describes an idealized action in which this thing would play an 'object' role.

inputs.name: identifier
inputs.help: The identifier property represents any kind of identifier for any kind of [[Thing]], such as ISBNs, GTIN codes, UUIDs etc. Schema.org provides dedicated properties for representing many of these, either as textual strings or as URL (URI) links. See [background notes](/docs/datamodel.html#identifierBg) for more details.

inputs.name: disambiguatingDescription
inputs.help: A sub property of description. A short description of the item used to disambiguate from other, similar items. Information from other properties (in particular, name) may be necessary for the description to be useful for disambiguation.

inputs.name: alternateName
inputs.help: An alias for the item.

inputs.name: additionalType
inputs.help: An additional type for the item, typically used for adding more specific types from external vocabularies in microdata syntax. This is a relationship between something and a class that the thing is in. In RDFa syntax, it is better to use the native RDFa syntax - the 'typeof' attribute - for multiple types. Schema.org tools may have only weaker understanding of extra types, in particular those defined externally.

inputs.name: subjectOf
inputs.help: A CreativeWork or Event about this Thing.

inputs.name: url
inputs.help: URL of the item.

inputs.name: description
inputs.help: A description of the item.

inputs.name: worksFor

inputs.name: awards

inputs.name: sibling
inputs.help: A sibling of the person.

inputs.name: birthDate
inputs.help: Date of birth.

inputs.name: address
inputs.help: Physical address of the item.

inputs.name: hasCredential

inputs.name: globalLocationNumber
inputs.help: The [Global Location Number](http://www.gs1.org/gln) (GLN, sometimes also referred to as International Location Number or ILN) of the respective organization, person, or place. The GLN is a 13-digit number used to identify parties and physical locations.

inputs.name: relatedTo
inputs.help: The most generic familial relation.

inputs.name: weight
inputs.help: The weight of the product or person.

inputs.name: birthPlace
inputs.help: The place where the person was born.

inputs.name: performerIn
inputs.help: Event that this person is a performer or participant in.

inputs.name: deathPlace
inputs.help: The place where the person died.

inputs.name: brand
inputs.help: The brand(s) associated with a product or service, or the brand(s) maintained by an organization or business person.

inputs.name: nationality

inputs.name: additionalName
inputs.help: An additional name for a Person, can be used for a middle name.

inputs.name: familyName
inputs.help: Family name. In the U.S., the last name of a Person.

inputs.name: email
inputs.help: Email address.

inputs.name: contactPoint
inputs.help: A contact point for a person or organization.

inputs.name: hasOccupation
inputs.help: The Person's occupation. For past professions, use Role for expressing dates.

inputs.name: publishingPrinciples
inputs.help:
The publishingPrinciples property indicates (typically via [[URL]]) a document describing the editorial principles of an [[Organization]] (or individual e.g. a [[Person]] writing a blog) that relate to their activities as a publisher, e.g. ethics or diversity policies. When applied to a [[CreativeWork]] (e.g. [[NewsArticle]]) the principles are those of the party primarily responsible for the creation of the [[CreativeWork]].

While such policies are most typically expressed in natural language, sometimes related information (e.g. indicating a [[funder]]) can be expressed using schema.org terminology.

inputs.name: knowsLanguage
inputs.help: Of a [[Person]], and less typically of an [[Organization]], to indicate a known language. We do not distinguish skill levels or reading/writing/speaking/signing here. Use language codes from the [IETF BCP 47 standard](http://tools.ietf.org/html/bcp47).

inputs.name: interactionStatistic
inputs.help: The number of interactions for the CreativeWork using the WebSite or SoftwareApplication. The most specific child type of InteractionCounter should be used.

inputs.name: knows
inputs.help: The most generic bi-directional social/work relation.

inputs.name: vatID
inputs.help: The Value-added Tax ID of the organization or person.

inputs.name: owns
inputs.help: Products owned by the organization or person.

inputs.name: siblings
inputs.help: A sibling of the person.

inputs.name: height
inputs.help: The height of the item.

inputs.name: duns
inputs.help: The Dun & Bradstreet DUNS number for identifying an organization or business person.

inputs.name: children
inputs.help: A child of the person.

inputs.name: award
inputs.help: An award won by or for this item.

inputs.name: homeLocation
inputs.help: A contact location for a person's residence.

inputs.name: telephone
inputs.help: The telephone number.

inputs.name: honorificSuffix
inputs.help: An honorific suffix following a Person's name such as M.D. /PhD/MSCSW.

inputs.name: colleagues
inputs.help: A colleague of the person.

inputs.name: seeks
inputs.help: A pointer to products or services sought by the organization or person (demand).

inputs.name: sponsor
inputs.help: A person or organization that supports a thing through a pledge, promise, or financial contribution. e.g. a sponsor of a Medical Study or a corporate sponsor of an event.

inputs.name: knowsAbout
inputs.help: Of a [[Person]], and less typically of an [[Organization]], to indicate a topic that is known about - suggesting possible expertise but not implying it. We do not distinguish skill levels here, or relate this to educational content, events, objectives or [[JobPosting]] descriptions.

inputs.name: funder
inputs.help: A person or organization that supports (sponsors) something through some kind of financial contribution.

inputs.name: taxID
inputs.help: The Tax / Fiscal ID of the organization or person, e.g. the TIN in the US or the CIF/NIF in Spain.

inputs.name: workLocation
inputs.help: A contact location for a person's place of work.

inputs.name: memberOf
inputs.help: An Organization (or ProgramMembership) to which this Person or Organization belongs.

inputs.name: hasPOS
inputs.help: Points-of-Sales operated by the organization or person.

inputs.name: callSign
inputs.help: A [callsign](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Call_sign), as used in broadcasting and radio communications to identify people, radio and TV stations, or vehicles.

inputs.name: gender
inputs.help: Gender of something, typically a [[Person]], but possibly also fictional characters, animals, etc. While http://schema.org/Male and http://schema.org/Female may be used, text strings are also acceptable for people who do not identify as a binary gender. The [[gender]] property can also be used in an extended sense to cover e.g. the gender of sports teams. As with the gender of individuals, we do not try to enumerate all possibilities. A mixed-gender [[SportsTeam]] can be indicated with a text value of "Mixed".

inputs.name: isicV4
inputs.help: The International Standard of Industrial Classification of All Economic Activities (ISIC), Revision 4 code for a particular organization, business person, or place.

inputs.name: jobTitle
inputs.help: The job title of the person (for example, Financial Manager).

inputs.name: parents
inputs.help: A parents of the person.

inputs.name: deathDate
inputs.help: Date of death.

inputs.name: colleague
inputs.help: A colleague of the person.

metadata.help:
A NewsArticle is an article whose content reports news, or provides background context and supporting materials for understanding the news.

A more detailed overview of [schema.org News markup](/docs/news.html) is also available.
metadata.name: NewsArticle

inputs.name: printPage
inputs.help: If this NewsArticle appears in print, this field indicates the name of the page on which the article is found. Please note that this field is intended for the exact page name (e.g. A5, B18).

inputs.name: printColumn
inputs.help: The number of the column in which the NewsArticle appears in the print edition.

inputs.name: dateline
inputs.help:
A [dateline](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dateline) is a brief piece of text included in news articles that describes where and when the story was written or filed though the date is often omitted. Sometimes only a placename is provided.

Structured representations of dateline-related information can also be expressed more explicitly using [[locationCreated]] (which represents where a work was created e.g. where a news report was written).  For location depicted or described in the content, use [[contentLocation]].

Dateline summaries are oriented more towards human readers than towards automated processing, and can vary substantially. Some examples: "BEIRUT, Lebanon, June 2.", "Paris, France", "December 19, 2017 11:43AM Reporting from Washington", "Beijing/Moscow", "QUEZON CITY, Philippines".

inputs.name: printEdition
inputs.help: The edition of the print product in which the NewsArticle appears.

inputs.name: printSection
inputs.help: If this NewsArticle appears in print, this field indicates the print section in which the article appeared.

metadata.help: A web page. Every web page is implicitly assumed to be declared to be of type WebPage, so the various properties about that webpage, such as breadcrumb may be used. We recommend explicit declaration if these properties are specified, but if they are found outside of an itemscope, they will be assumed to be about the page.
metadata.name: WebPage

inputs.name: significantLinks
inputs.help: The most significant URLs on the page. Typically, these are the non-navigation links that are clicked on the most.

inputs.help: People or organizations that have reviewed the content on this web page for accuracy and/or completeness.

inputs.name: speakable
inputs.help:
Indicates sections of a Web page that are particularly 'speakable' in the sense of being highlighted as being especially appropriate for text-to-speech conversion. Other sections of a page may also be usefully spoken in particular circumstances; the 'speakable' property serves to indicate the parts most likely to be generally useful for speech.

The *speakable* property can be repeated an arbitrary number of times, with three kinds of possible 'content-locator' values:

1.) *id-value* URL references - uses *id-value* of an element in the page being annotated. The simplest use of *speakable* has (potentially relative) URL values, referencing identified sections of the document concerned.

2.) CSS Selectors - addresses content in the annotated page, eg. via class attribute. Use the [[cssSelector]] property.

3.)  XPaths - addresses content via XPaths (assuming an XML view of the content). Use the [[xpath]] property.


For more sophisticated markup of speakable sections beyond simple ID references, either CSS selectors or XPath expressions to pick out document section(s) as speakable. For this
we define a supporting type, [[SpeakableSpecification]]  which is defined to be a possible value of the *speakable* property.

inputs.name: mainContentOfPage
inputs.help: Indicates if this web page element is the main subject of the page.

inputs.name: primaryImageOfPage
inputs.help: Indicates the main image on the page.

inputs.name: significantLink
inputs.help: One of the more significant URLs on the page. Typically, these are the non-navigation links that are clicked on the most.

inputs.name: lastReviewed
inputs.help: Date on which the content on this web page was last reviewed for accuracy and/or completeness.

inputs.name: specialty
inputs.help: One of the domain specialities to which this web page's content applies.

inputs.name: relatedLink
inputs.help: A link related to this web page, for example to other related web pages.

inputs.name: breadcrumb
inputs.help: A set of links that can help a user understand and navigate a website hierarchy.

metadata.help:
The [[ReportageNewsArticle]] type is a subtype of [[NewsArticle]] representing
 news articles which are the result of journalistic news reporting conventions.

In practice many news publishers produce a wide variety of article types, many of which might be considered a [[NewsArticle]] but not a [[ReportageNewsArticle]]. For example, opinion pieces, reviews, analysis, sponsored or satirical articles, or articles that combine several of these elements.

The [[ReportageNewsArticle]] type is based on a stricter ideal for "news" as a work of journalism, with articles based on factual information either observed or verified by the author, or reported and verified from knowledgeable sources.  This often includes perspectives from multiple viewpoints on a particular issue (distinguishing news reports from public relations or propaganda).  News reports in the [[ReportageNewsArticle]] sense de-emphasize the opinion of the author, with commentary and value judgements typically expressed elsewhere.

A [[ReportageNewsArticle]] which goes deeper into analysis can also be marked with an additional type of [[AnalysisNewsArticle]].
metadata.name: ReportageNewsArticle

metadata.help: An observational study is a type of medical study that attempts to infer the possible effect of a treatment through observation of a cohort of subjects over a period of time. In an observational study, the assignment of subjects into treatment groups versus control groups is outside the control of the investigator. This is in contrast with controlled studies, such as the randomized controlled trials represented by MedicalTrial, where each subject is randomly assigned to a treatment group or a control group before the start of the treatment.

metadata.help:
A CreativeWorkSeries in schema.org is a group of related items, typically but not necessarily of the same kind. CreativeWorkSeries are usually organized into some order, often chronological. Unlike [[ItemList]] which is a general purpose data structure for lists of things, the emphasis with CreativeWorkSeries is on published materials (written e.g. books and periodicals, or media such as tv, radio and games).

Specific subtypes are available for describing [[TVSeries]], [[RadioSeries]], [[MovieSeries]], [[BookSeries]], [[Periodical]] and [[VideoGameSeries]]. In each case, the [[hasPart]] / [[isPartOf]] properties can be used to relate the CreativeWorkSeries to its parts. The general CreativeWorkSeries type serves largely just to organize these more specific and practical subtypes.

It is common for properties applicable to an item from the series to be usefully applied to the containing group. Schema.org attempts to anticipate some of these cases, but publishers should be free to apply properties of the series parts to the series as a whole wherever they seem appropriate.
metadata.name: CreativeWorkSeries
