metadata.help:
A series of [[Event]]s. Included events can relate with the series using the [[superEvent]] property.

An EventSeries is a collection of events that share some unifying characteristic. For example, "The Olympic Games" is a series, which
is repeated regularly. The "2012 London Olympics" can be presented both as an [[Event]] in the series "Olympic Games", and as an
[[EventSeries]] that included a number of sporting competitions as Events.

The nature of the association between the events in an [[EventSeries]] can vary, but typical examples could
include a thematic event series (e.g. topical meetups or classes), or a series of regular events that share a location, attendee group and/or organizers.

EventSeries has been defined as a kind of Event to make it easy for publishers to use it in an Event context without
worrying about which kinds of series are really event-like enough to call an Event. In general an EventSeries
may seem more Event-like when the period of time is compact and when aspects such as location are fixed, but
it may also sometimes prove useful to describe a longer-term series as an Event.
metadata.name: EventSeries

metadata.help:
A grant, typically financial or otherwise quantifiable, of resources. Typically a [[funder]] sponsors some [[MonetaryAmount]] to an [[Organization]] or [[Person]],
    sometimes not necessarily via a dedicated or long-lived [[Project]], resulting in one or more outputs, or [[fundedItem]]s. For financial sponsorship, indicate the [[funder]] of a [[MonetaryGrant]]. For non-financial support, indicate [[sponsor]] of [[Grant]]s of resources (e.g. office space).

Grants support  activities directed towards some agreed collective goals, often but not always organized as [[Project]]s. Long-lived projects are sometimes sponsored by a variety of grants over time, but it is also common for a project to be associated with a single grant.

The amount of a [[Grant]] is represented using [[amount]] as a [[MonetaryAmount]].

metadata.name: MedicalCondition

inputs.name: signOrSymptom
inputs.help: A sign or symptom of this condition. Signs are objective or physically observable manifestations of the medical condition while symptoms are the subjective experience of the medical condition.

inputs.name: drug
inputs.help: Specifying a drug or medicine used in a medication procedure

inputs.name: typicalTest
inputs.help: A medical test typically performed given this condition.

inputs.name: secondaryPrevention
inputs.help: A preventative therapy used to prevent reoccurrence of the medical condition after an initial episode of the condition.

inputs.name: possibleComplication
inputs.help: A possible unexpected and unfavorable evolution of a medical condition. Complications may include worsening of the signs or symptoms of the disease, extension of the condition to other organ systems, etc.

inputs.name: naturalProgression
inputs.help: The expected progression of the condition if it is not treated and allowed to progress naturally.

inputs.name: primaryPrevention
inputs.help: A preventative therapy used to prevent an initial occurrence of the medical condition, such as vaccination.

inputs.name: riskFactor
inputs.help: A modifiable or non-modifiable factor that increases the risk of a patient contracting this condition, e.g. age,  coexisting condition.

inputs.name: expectedPrognosis
inputs.help: The likely outcome in either the short term or long term of the medical condition.

inputs.name: possibleTreatment
inputs.help: A possible treatment to address this condition, sign or symptom.

inputs.name: status
inputs.help: The status of the study (enumerated).

inputs.name: epidemiology
inputs.help: The characteristics of associated patients, such as age, gender, race etc.

inputs.name: associatedAnatomy
inputs.help: The anatomy of the underlying organ system or structures associated with this entity.

inputs.name: pathophysiology
inputs.help: Changes in the normal mechanical, physical, and biochemical functions that are associated with this activity or condition.

inputs.name: differentialDiagnosis
inputs.help: One of a set of differential diagnoses for the condition. Specifically, a closely-related or competing diagnosis typically considered later in the cognitive process whereby this medical condition is distinguished from others most likely responsible for a similar collection of signs and symptoms to reach the most parsimonious diagnosis or diagnoses in a patient.

inputs.name: stage
inputs.help: The stage of the condition, if applicable.

metadata.help:
An offer to transfer some rights to an item or to provide a service  for example, an offer to sell tickets to an event, to rent the DVD of a movie, to stream a TV show over the internet, to repair a motorcycle, or to loan a book.

Note: As the [[businessFunction]] property, which identifies the form of offer (e.g. sell, lease, repair, dispose), defaults to http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#Sell; an Offer without a defined businessFunction value can be assumed to be an offer to sell.

For [GTIN](http://www.gs1.org/barcodes/technical/idkeys/gtin)-related fields, see [Check Digit calculator](http://www.gs1.org/barcodes/support/check_digit_calculator) and [validation guide](http://www.gs1us.org/resources/standards/gtin-validation-guide) from [GS1](http://www.gs1.org/).
metadata.name: Offer

inputs.name: gtin13
inputs.help: The GTIN-13 code of the product, or the product to which the offer refers. This is equivalent to 13-digit ISBN codes and EAN UCC-13. Former 12-digit UPC codes can be converted into a GTIN-13 code by simply adding a preceding zero. See [GS1 GTIN Summary](http://www.gs1.org/barcodes/technical/idkeys/gtin) for more details.

inputs.name: itemOffered
inputs.help: An item being offered (or demanded). The transactional nature of the offer or demand is documented using [[businessFunction]], e.g. sell, lease etc. While several common expected types are listed explicitly in this definition, others can be used. Using a second type, such as Product or a subtype of Product, can clarify the nature of the offer.

inputs.name: deliveryLeadTime
inputs.help: The typical delay between the receipt of the order and the goods either leaving the warehouse or being prepared for pickup, in case the delivery method is on site pickup.

inputs.name: eligibleQuantity
inputs.help: The interval and unit of measurement of ordering quantities for which the offer or price specification is valid. This allows e.g. specifying that a certain freight charge is valid only for a certain quantity.

inputs.name: availability
inputs.help: The availability of this item—for example In stock, Out of stock, Pre-order, etc.

inputs.name: price
inputs.help:
The offer price of a product, or of a price component when attached to PriceSpecification and its subtypes.

Usage guidelines:

* Use the [[priceCurrency]] property (with standard formats: [ISO 4217 currency format](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_4217) e.g. "USD"; [Ticker symbol](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_cryptocurrencies) for cryptocurrencies e.g. "BTC"; well known names for [Local Exchange Tradings Systems](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Local_exchange_trading_system) (LETS) and other currency types e.g. "Ithaca HOUR") instead of including [ambiguous symbols](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dollar_sign#Currencies_that_use_the_dollar_or_peso_sign) such as '$' in the value.
* Use '.' (Unicode 'FULL STOP' (U+002E)) rather than ',' to indicate a decimal point. Avoid using these symbols as a readability separator.
* Note that both [RDFa](http://www.w3.org/TR/xhtml-rdfa-primer/#using-the-content-attribute) and Microdata syntax allow the use of a "content=" attribute for publishing simple machine-readable values alongside more human-friendly formatting.
* Use values from 0123456789 (Unicode 'DIGIT ZERO' (U+0030) to 'DIGIT NINE' (U+0039)) rather than superficially similiar Unicode symbols.

inputs.name: addOn
inputs.help: An additional offer that can only be obtained in combination with the first base offer (e.g. supplements and extensions that are available for a surcharge).

inputs.name: serialNumber
inputs.help: The serial number or any alphanumeric identifier of a particular product. When attached to an offer, it is a shortcut for the serial number of the product included in the offer.

inputs.name: review
inputs.help: A review of the item.

inputs.name: offeredBy
inputs.help: A pointer to the organization or person making the offer.

inputs.name: gtin
inputs.help: A Global Trade Item Number ([GTIN](https://www.gs1.org/standards/id-keys/gtin)). GTINs identify trade items, including products and services, using numeric identification codes. The [[gtin]] property generalizes the earlier [[gtin8]], [[gtin12]], [[gtin13]], and [[gtin14]] properties. The GS1 [digital link specifications](https://www.gs1.org/standards/Digital-Link/) express GTINs as URLs. A correct [[gtin]] value should be a valid GTIN, which means that it should be an all-numeric string of either 8, 12, 13 or 14 digits, or a "GS1 Digital Link" URL based on such a string. The numeric component should also have a [valid GS1 check digit](https://www.gs1.org/services/check-digit-calculator) and meet the other rules for valid GTINs. See also [GS1's GTIN Summary](http://www.gs1.org/barcodes/technical/idkeys/gtin) and [Wikipedia](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Global_Trade_Item_Number) for more details. Left-padding of the gtin values is not required or encouraged.

inputs.name: priceCurrency
inputs.help: The currency of the price, or a price component when attached to [[PriceSpecification]] and its subtypes.\n\nUse standard formats: [ISO 4217 currency format](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_4217) e.g. "USD"; [Ticker symbol](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_cryptocurrencies) for cryptocurrencies e.g. "BTC"; well known names for [Local Exchange Tradings Systems](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Local_exchange_trading_system) (LETS) and other currency types e.g. "Ithaca HOUR".

inputs.name: shippingDetails
inputs.help: Indicates information about the shipping policies and options associated with an [[Offer]].

inputs.name: itemCondition
inputs.help: A predefined value from OfferItemCondition or a textual description of the condition of the product or service, or the products or services included in the offer.

inputs.name: gtin14
inputs.help: The GTIN-14 code of the product, or the product to which the offer refers. See [GS1 GTIN Summary](http://www.gs1.org/barcodes/technical/idkeys/gtin) for more details.

inputs.name: reviews
inputs.help: Review of the item.

inputs.name: includesObject
inputs.help: This links to a node or nodes indicating the exact quantity of the products included in  an [[Offer]] or [[ProductCollection]].

inputs.name: advanceBookingRequirement
inputs.help: The amount of time that is required between accepting the offer and the actual usage of the resource or service.

inputs.name: availableAtOrFrom
inputs.help: The place(s) from which the offer can be obtained (e.g. store locations).

inputs.name: ineligibleRegion
inputs.help: The ISO 3166-1 (ISO 3166-1 alpha-2) or ISO 3166-2 code, the place, or the GeoShape for the geo-political region(s) for which the offer or delivery charge specification is not valid, e.g. a region where the transaction is not allowed.\n\nSee also [[eligibleRegion]].

inputs.name: eligibleDuration
inputs.help: The duration for which the given offer is valid.

inputs.name: businessFunction
inputs.help: The business function (e.g. sell, lease, repair, dispose) of the offer or component of a bundle (TypeAndQuantityNode). The default is http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#Sell.

inputs.name: priceSpecification
inputs.help: One or more detailed price specifications, indicating the unit price and delivery or payment charges.

inputs.name: warranty
inputs.help: The warranty promise(s) included in the offer.

inputs.name: eligibleTransactionVolume
inputs.help: The transaction volume, in a monetary unit, for which the offer or price specification is valid, e.g. for indicating a minimal purchasing volume, to express free shipping above a certain order volume, or to limit the acceptance of credit cards to purchases to a certain minimal amount.

inputs.name: validThrough
inputs.help: The date after when the item is not valid. For example the end of an offer, salary period, or a period of opening hours.

inputs.name: aggregateRating
inputs.help: The overall rating, based on a collection of reviews or ratings, of the item.

inputs.name: gtin8
inputs.help: The [GTIN-8](http://apps.gs1.org/GDD/glossary/Pages/GTIN-8.aspx) code of the product, or the product to which the offer refers. This code is also known as EAN/UCC-8 or 8-digit EAN. See [GS1 GTIN Summary](http://www.gs1.org/barcodes/technical/idkeys/gtin) for more details.

inputs.name: leaseLength
inputs.help: Length of the lease for some [[Accommodation]], either particular to some [[Offer]] or in some cases intrinsic to the property.

inputs.name: availabilityEnds
inputs.help: The end of the availability of the product or service included in the offer.

inputs.name: eligibleCustomerType
inputs.help: The type(s) of customers for which the given offer is valid.

inputs.name: priceValidUntil
inputs.help: The date after which the price is no longer available.

inputs.name: inventoryLevel
inputs.help: The current approximate inventory level for the item or items.

inputs.name: availableDeliveryMethod
inputs.help: The delivery method(s) available for this offer.

inputs.name: seller
inputs.help: An entity which offers (sells / leases / lends / loans) the services / goods.  A seller may also be a provider.

inputs.name: mpn
inputs.help: The Manufacturer Part Number (MPN) of the product, or the product to which the offer refers.

inputs.name: eligibleRegion
inputs.help: The ISO 3166-1 (ISO 3166-1 alpha-2) or ISO 3166-2 code, the place, or the GeoShape for the geo-political region(s) for which the offer or delivery charge specification is valid.\n\nSee also [[ineligibleRegion]].

inputs.name: availabilityStarts
inputs.help: The beginning of the availability of the product or service included in the offer.

inputs.name: validFrom
inputs.help: The date when the item becomes valid.

inputs.name: gtin12
inputs.help: The GTIN-12 code of the product, or the product to which the offer refers. The GTIN-12 is the 12-digit GS1 Identification Key composed of a U.P.C. Company Prefix, Item Reference, and Check Digit used to identify trade items. See [GS1 GTIN Summary](http://www.gs1.org/barcodes/technical/idkeys/gtin) for more details.

inputs.name: areaServed
inputs.help: The geographic area where a service or offered item is provided.

inputs.name: category
inputs.help: A category for the item. Greater signs or slashes can be used to informally indicate a category hierarchy.

inputs.name: acceptedPaymentMethod
inputs.help: The payment method(s) accepted by seller for this offer.

inputs.name: sku
inputs.help: The Stock Keeping Unit (SKU), i.e. a merchant-specific identifier for a product or service, or the product to which the offer refers.

metadata.help:
A [[CompleteDataFeed]] is a [[DataFeed]] whose standard representation includes content for every item currently in the feed.

This is the equivalent of Atom's element as defined in Feed Paging and Archiving [RFC 5005](https://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc5005), For example (and as defined for Atom), when using data from a feed that represents a collection of items that varies over time (e.g. "Top Twenty Records") there is no need to have newer entries mixed in alongside older, obsolete entries. By marking this feed as a CompleteDataFeed, old entries can be safely discarded when the feed is refreshed, since we can assume the feed has provided descriptions for all current items.
metadata.name: CompleteDataFeed

metadata.help: A structured value representing a price or price range. Typically, only the subclasses of this type are used for markup. It is recommended to use [[MonetaryAmount]] to describe independent amounts of money such as a salary, credit card limits, etc.

inputs.name: eligibleQuantity
inputs.help: The interval and unit of measurement of ordering quantities for which the offer or price specification is valid. This allows e.g. specifying that a certain freight charge is valid only for a certain quantity.

inputs.name: price
inputs.help:
The offer price of a product, or of a price component when attached to PriceSpecification and its subtypes.

Usage guidelines:

* Use the [[priceCurrency]] property (with standard formats: [ISO 4217 currency format](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_4217) e.g. "USD"; [Ticker symbol](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_cryptocurrencies) for cryptocurrencies e.g. "BTC"; well known names for [Local Exchange Tradings Systems](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Local_exchange_trading_system) (LETS) and other currency types e.g. "Ithaca HOUR") instead of including [ambiguous symbols](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dollar_sign#Currencies_that_use_the_dollar_or_peso_sign) such as '$' in the value.
* Use '.' (Unicode 'FULL STOP' (U+002E)) rather than ',' to indicate a decimal point. Avoid using these symbols as a readability separator.
* Note that both [RDFa](http://www.w3.org/TR/xhtml-rdfa-primer/#using-the-content-attribute) and Microdata syntax allow the use of a "content=" attribute for publishing simple machine-readable values alongside more human-friendly formatting.
* Use values from 0123456789 (Unicode 'DIGIT ZERO' (U+0030) to 'DIGIT NINE' (U+0039)) rather than superficially similiar Unicode symbols.

inputs.name: priceCurrency
inputs.help: The currency of the price, or a price component when attached to [[PriceSpecification]] and its subtypes.\n\nUse standard formats: [ISO 4217 currency format](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_4217) e.g. "USD"; [Ticker symbol](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_cryptocurrencies) for cryptocurrencies e.g. "BTC"; well known names for [Local Exchange Tradings Systems](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Local_exchange_trading_system) (LETS) and other currency types e.g. "Ithaca HOUR".

inputs.name: eligibleTransactionVolume
inputs.help: The transaction volume, in a monetary unit, for which the offer or price specification is valid, e.g. for indicating a minimal purchasing volume, to express free shipping above a certain order volume, or to limit the acceptance of credit cards to purchases to a certain minimal amount.

inputs.name: validThrough
inputs.help: The date after when the item is not valid. For example the end of an offer, salary period, or a period of opening hours.

inputs.name: valueAddedTaxIncluded
inputs.help: Specifies whether the applicable value-added tax (VAT) is included in the price specification or not.

inputs.name: valueReference
inputs.help: A pointer to a secondary value that provides additional information on the original value, e.g. a reference temperature.

inputs.name: additionalProperty
inputs.help: A property-value pair representing an additional characteristics of the entitity, e.g. a product feature or another characteristic for which there is no matching property in schema.org.\n\nNote: Publishers should be aware that applications designed to use specific schema.org properties (e.g. http://schema.org/width, http://schema.org/color, http://schema.org/gtin13, ...) will typically expect such data to be provided using those properties, rather than using the generic property/value mechanism.

inputs.name: unitText
inputs.help: A string or text indicating the unit of measurement. Useful if you cannot provide a standard unit code for unitCode.

inputs.name: value
inputs.help:
The value of the quantitative value or property value node.

* For [[QuantitativeValue]] and [[MonetaryAmount]], the recommended type for values is 'Number'.
* For [[PropertyValue]], it can be 'Text;', 'Number', 'Boolean', or 'StructuredValue'.
* Use values from 0123456789 (Unicode 'DIGIT ZERO' (U+0030) to 'DIGIT NINE' (U+0039)) rather than superficially similiar Unicode symbols.
* Use '.' (Unicode 'FULL STOP' (U+002E)) rather than ',' to indicate a decimal point. Avoid using these symbols as a readability separator.

inputs.name: maxValue

metadata.help: A HyperToEntry is an item within a [[HyperToc]], which represents a hypertext table of contents for complex media objects, such as [[VideoObject]], [[AudioObject]]. The media object itself is indicated using [[associatedMedia]]. Each section of interest within that content can be described with a [[HyperTocEntry]], with associated [[startOffset]] and [[endOffset]]. When several entries are all from the same file, [[associatedMedia]] is used on the overarching [[HyperTocEntry]]; if the content has been split into multiple files, they can be referenced using [[associatedMedia]] on each [[HyperTocEntry]].

inputs.name: smokingAllowed
inputs.help: Indicates whether it is allowed to smoke in the place, e.g. in the restaurant, hotel or hotel room.

inputs.name: containedIn
inputs.help: The basic containment relation between a place and one that contains it.

inputs.name: geoOverlaps
inputs.help: Represents a relationship between two geometries (or the places they represent), relating a geometry to another that geospatially overlaps it, i.e. they have some but not all points in common. As defined in [DE-9IM](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/DE-9IM).

inputs.name: maps
inputs.help: A URL to a map of the place.

inputs.name: branchCode
inputs.help: A short textual code (also called "store code") that uniquely identifies a place of business. The code is typically assigned by the parentOrganization and used in structured URLs.\n\nFor example, in the URL http://www.starbucks.co.uk/store-locator/etc/detail/3047 the code "3047" is a branchCode for a particular branch.

inputs.name: address
inputs.help: Physical address of the item.

inputs.name: openingHoursSpecification
inputs.help: The opening hours of a certain place.

inputs.name: globalLocationNumber
inputs.help: The [Global Location Number](http://www.gs1.org/gln) (GLN, sometimes also referred to as International Location Number or ILN) of the respective organization, person, or place. The GLN is a 13-digit number used to identify parties and physical locations.

inputs.name: geoCrosses
inputs.help: Represents a relationship between two geometries (or the places they represent), relating a geometry to another that crosses it: "a crosses b: they have some but not all interior points in common, and the dimension of the intersection is less than that of at least one of them". As defined in [DE-9IM](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/DE-9IM).

inputs.name: review
inputs.help: A review of the item.

inputs.name: photos
inputs.help: Photographs of this place.

inputs.name: specialOpeningHoursSpecification
inputs.help: The special opening hours of a certain place.\n\nUse this to explicitly override general opening hours brought in scope by [[openingHoursSpecification]] or [[openingHours]].

inputs.name: slogan
inputs.help: A slogan or motto associated with the item.

inputs.name: geoContains
inputs.help: Represents a relationship between two geometries (or the places they represent), relating a containing geometry to a contained geometry. "a contains b iff no points of b lie in the exterior of a, and at least one point of the interior of b lies in the interior of a". As defined in [DE-9IM](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/DE-9IM).

inputs.name: events
inputs.help: Upcoming or past events associated with this place or organization.

inputs.name: hasDriveThroughService
inputs.help: Indicates whether some facility (e.g. [[FoodEstablishment]], [[CovidTestingFacility]]) offers a service that can be used by driving through in a car. In the case of [[CovidTestingFacility]] such facilities could potentially help with social distancing from other potentially-infected users.

inputs.name: geoTouches
inputs.help: Represents spatial relations in which two geometries (or the places they represent) touch: they have at least one boundary point in common, but no interior points." (a symmetric relationship, as defined in [DE-9IM](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/DE-9IM) )

inputs.name: hasMap
inputs.help: A URL to a map of the place.

inputs.name: reviews
inputs.help: Review of the item.

inputs.name: additionalProperty
inputs.help: A property-value pair representing an additional characteristics of the entitity, e.g. a product feature or another characteristic for which there is no matching property in schema.org.\n\nNote: Publishers should be aware that applications designed to use specific schema.org properties (e.g. http://schema.org/width, http://schema.org/color, http://schema.org/gtin13, ...) will typically expect such data to be provided using those properties, rather than using the generic property/value mechanism.

inputs.name: geoCoveredBy
inputs.help: Represents a relationship between two geometries (or the places they represent), relating a geometry to another that covers it. As defined in [DE-9IM](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/DE-9IM).

inputs.name: geoDisjoint
inputs.help: Represents spatial relations in which two geometries (or the places they represent) are topologically disjoint: they have no point in common. They form a set of disconnected geometries." (a symmetric relationship, as defined in [DE-9IM](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/DE-9IM))

inputs.name: geoEquals
inputs.help: Represents spatial relations in which two geometries (or the places they represent) are topologically equal, as defined in [DE-9IM](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/DE-9IM). "Two geometries are topologically equal if their interiors intersect and no part of the interior or boundary of one geometry intersects the exterior of the other" (a symmetric relationship)

inputs.name: publicAccess
inputs.help: A flag to signal that the [[Place]] is open to public visitors.  If this property is omitted there is no assumed default boolean value

inputs.name: tourBookingPage
inputs.help: A page providing information on how to book a tour of some [[Place]], such as an [[Accommodation]] or [[ApartmentComplex]] in a real estate setting, as well as other kinds of tours as appropriate.

inputs.name: geo
inputs.help: The geo coordinates of the place.

inputs.name: event
inputs.help: Upcoming or past event associated with this place, organization, or action.

inputs.name: telephone
inputs.help: The telephone number.

inputs.name: longitude
inputs.help: The longitude of a location. For example ```-122.08585``` ([WGS 84](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/World_Geodetic_System)).

inputs.name: containedInPlace
inputs.help: The basic containment relation between a place and one that contains it.

inputs.name: geoIntersects
inputs.help: Represents spatial relations in which two geometries (or the places they represent) have at least one point in common. As defined in [DE-9IM](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/DE-9IM).

inputs.name: aggregateRating
inputs.help: The overall rating, based on a collection of reviews or ratings, of the item.

inputs.name: containsPlace
inputs.help: The basic containment relation between a place and another that it contains.

inputs.name: geoWithin
inputs.help: Represents a relationship between two geometries (or the places they represent), relating a geometry to one that contains it, i.e. it is inside (i.e. within) its interior. As defined in [DE-9IM](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/DE-9IM).

inputs.name: logo
inputs.help: An associated logo.

inputs.name: maximumAttendeeCapacity
inputs.help: The total number of individuals that may attend an event or venue.

inputs.name: map
inputs.help: A URL to a map of the place.

inputs.name: isicV4
inputs.help: The International Standard of Industrial Classification of All Economic Activities (ISIC), Revision 4 code for a particular organization, business person, or place.

inputs.name: isAccessibleForFree
inputs.help: A flag to signal that the item, event, or place is accessible for free.

inputs.name: geoCovers
inputs.help: Represents a relationship between two geometries (or the places they represent), relating a covering geometry to a covered geometry. "Every point of b is a point of (the interior or boundary of) a". As defined in [DE-9IM](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/DE-9IM).

inputs.name: amenityFeature
inputs.help: An amenity feature (e.g. a characteristic or service) of the Accommodation. This generic property does not make a statement about whether the feature is included in an offer for the main accommodation or available at extra costs.

inputs.name: faxNumber
inputs.help: The fax number.

inputs.name: photo
inputs.help: A photograph of this place.

inputs.name: latitude
inputs.help: The latitude of a location. For example ```37.42242``` ([WGS 84](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/World_Geodetic_System)).

metadata.help: One or more messages between organizations or people on a particular topic. Individual messages can be linked to the conversation with isPartOf or hasPart properties.
metadata.name: Conversation

metadata.help:
The act of un-registering from a service.

Related actions:

* [[RegisterAction]]: antonym of UnRegisterAction.
* [[LeaveAction]]: Unlike LeaveAction, UnRegisterAction implies that you are unregistering from a service you werer previously registered, rather than leaving a team/group of people.
metadata.name: UnRegisterAction

metadata.help:
The act of notifying someone that a future event/action is going to happen as expected.

Related actions:

* [[CancelAction]]: The antonym of ConfirmAction.
metadata.name: ConfirmAction

metadata.help:
The business function specifies the type of activity or access (i.e., the bundle of rights) offered by the organization or business person through the offer. Typical are sell, rental or lease, maintenance or repair, manufacture / produce, recycle / dispose, engineering / construction, or installation. Proprietary specifications of access rights are also instances of this class.

Commonly used values:

* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#ConstructionInstallation
* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#Dispose
* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#LeaseOut
* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#Maintain
* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#ProvideService
* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#Repair
* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#Sell
* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#Buy
metadata.name: BusinessFunction

metadata.help: Properties that take Energy as values are of the form '<Number> <Energy unit of measure>'.
metadata.name: Energy

metadata.help: Web applications.
metadata.name: WebApplication

inputs.name: browserRequirements
inputs.help: Specifies browser requirements in human-readable text. For example, 'requires HTML5 support'.

metadata.help: Status of a game server.
metadata.name: GameServerStatus

metadata.help: An account that allows an investor to deposit funds and place investment orders with a licensed broker or brokerage firm.
metadata.name: BrokerageAccount

metadata.help: A video game series.
metadata.name: VideoGameSeries

inputs.name: numberOfSeasons
inputs.help: The number of seasons in this series.

inputs.name: playMode
inputs.help: Indicates whether this game is multi-player, co-op or single-player.  The game can be marked as multi-player, co-op and single-player at the same time.

inputs.name: directors
inputs.help: A director of e.g. tv, radio, movie, video games etc. content. Directors can be associated with individual items or with a series, episode, clip.

inputs.name: gamePlatform
inputs.help: The electronic systems used to play video games.

inputs.name: quest
inputs.help: The task that a player-controlled character, or group of characters may complete in order to gain a reward.

inputs.name: gameItem
inputs.help: An item is an object within the game world that can be collected by a player or, occasionally, a non-player character.

inputs.name: seasons
inputs.help: A season in a media series.

inputs.name: numberOfPlayers
inputs.help: Indicate how many people can play this game (minimum, maximum, or range).

inputs.name: characterAttribute
inputs.help: A piece of data that represents a particular aspect of a fictional character (skill, power, character points, advantage, disadvantage).

inputs.name: season
inputs.help: A season in a media series.

inputs.name: numberOfEpisodes
inputs.help: The number of episodes in this season or series.

inputs.name: musicBy
inputs.help: The composer of the soundtrack.

inputs.name: productionCompany
inputs.help: The production company or studio responsible for the item e.g. series, video game, episode etc.

inputs.name: episode
inputs.help: An episode of a tv, radio or game media within a series or season.

inputs.name: trailer
inputs.help: The trailer of a movie or tv/radio series, season, episode, etc.

inputs.name: cheatCode
inputs.help: Cheat codes to the game.

inputs.name: gameLocation
inputs.help: Real or fictional location of the game (or part of game).

inputs.name: actors
inputs.help: An actor, e.g. in tv, radio, movie, video games etc. Actors can be associated with individual items or with a series, episode, clip.

inputs.name: actor
inputs.help: An actor, e.g. in tv, radio, movie, video games etc., or in an event. Actors can be associated with individual items or with a series, episode, clip.

inputs.name: containsSeason
inputs.help: A season that is part of the media series.

inputs.name: director
inputs.help: A director of e.g. tv, radio, movie, video gaming etc. content, or of an event. Directors can be associated with individual items or with a series, episode, clip.

inputs.name: episodes
inputs.help: An episode of a TV/radio series or season.

metadata.help: The act of notifying someone of information pertinent to them, with no expectation of a response.
metadata.name: InformAction

inputs.name: event
inputs.help: Upcoming or past event associated with this place, organization, or action.

metadata.help: A specific strength in which a medical drug is available in a specific country.
metadata.name: DrugStrength

inputs.name: strengthValue
inputs.help: The value of an active ingredient's strength, e.g. 325.

inputs.name: activeIngredient
inputs.help: An active ingredient, typically chemical compounds and/or biologic substances.

inputs.name: maximumIntake
inputs.help: Recommended intake of this supplement for a given population as defined by a specific recommending authority.

inputs.name: availableIn
inputs.help: The location in which the strength is available.

inputs.name: strengthUnit
inputs.help: The units of an active ingredient's strength, e.g. mg.

metadata.help: A monetary value or range. This type can be used to describe an amount of money such as $50 USD, or a range as in describing a bank account being suitable for a balance between 1,000 and 1,000,000 GBP, or the value of a salary, etc. It is recommended to use [[PriceSpecification]] Types to describe the price of an Offer, Invoice, etc.
metadata.name: MonetaryAmount

inputs.name: validThrough
inputs.help: The date after when the item is not valid. For example the end of an offer, salary period, or a period of opening hours.

inputs.name: value
inputs.help:
The value of the quantitative value or property value node.

* For [[QuantitativeValue]] and [[MonetaryAmount]], the recommended type for values is 'Number'.
* For [[PropertyValue]], it can be 'Text;', 'Number', 'Boolean', or 'StructuredValue'.
* Use values from 0123456789 (Unicode 'DIGIT ZERO' (U+0030) to 'DIGIT NINE' (U+0039)) rather than superficially similiar Unicode symbols.
* Use '.' (Unicode 'FULL STOP' (U+002E)) rather than ',' to indicate a decimal point. Avoid using these symbols as a readability separator.

inputs.name: maxValue
inputs.help: The upper value of some characteristic or property.

inputs.name: minValue
inputs.help: The lower value of some characteristic or property.

inputs.name: currency
inputs.help: The currency in which the monetary amount is expressed.\n\nUse standard formats: [ISO 4217 currency format](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_4217) e.g. "USD"; [Ticker symbol](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_cryptocurrencies) for cryptocurrencies e.g. "BTC"; well known names for [Local Exchange Tradings Systems](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Local_exchange_trading_system) (LETS) and other currency types e.g. "Ithaca HOUR".

inputs.name: validFrom
inputs.help: The date when the item becomes valid.

metadata.help: A picture or diagram made with a pencil, pen, or crayon rather than paint.
metadata.name: Drawing

metadata.help: A specific object or file containing a Legislation. Note that the same Legislation can be published in multiple files. For example, a digitally signed PDF, a plain PDF and an HTML version.
metadata.name: LegislationObject

inputs.name: legislationLegalValue
inputs.help: The legal value of this legislation file. The same legislation can be written in multiple files with different legal values. Typically a digitally signed PDF have a "stronger" legal value than the HTML file of the same act.

metadata.help:
OfferShippingDetails represents information about shipping destinations.

Multiple of these entities can be used to represent different shipping rates for different destinations:

One entity for Alaska/Hawaii. A different one for continental US.A different one for all France.

Multiple of these entities can be used to represent different shipping costs and delivery times.

Two entities that are identical but differ in rate and time:

e.g. Cheaper and slower: $5 in 5-7days
or Fast and expensive: $15 in 1-2 days
metadata.name: OfferShippingDetails

inputs.name: transitTimeLabel
inputs.help: Label to match an [[OfferShippingDetails]] with a [[DeliveryTimeSettings]] (within the context of a [[shippingSettingsLink]] cross-reference).

inputs.name: shippingRate
inputs.help: The shipping rate is the cost of shipping to the specified destination. Typically, the maxValue and currency values (of the [[MonetaryAmount]]) are most appropriate.

inputs.name: shippingLabel
inputs.help: Label to match an [[OfferShippingDetails]] with a [[ShippingRateSettings]] (within the context of a [[shippingSettingsLink]] cross-reference).

inputs.name: deliveryTime
inputs.help: The total delay between the receipt of the order and the goods reaching the final customer.

inputs.name: doesNotShip
inputs.help: Indicates when shipping to a particular [[shippingDestination]] is not available.

inputs.name: shippingDestination
inputs.help: indicates (possibly multiple) shipping destinations. These can be defined in several ways e.g. postalCode ranges.

inputs.name: shippingSettingsLink
inputs.help: Link to a page containing [[ShippingRateSettings]] and [[DeliveryTimeSettings]] details.

metadata.help: Rigid connective tissue that comprises up the skeletal structure of the human body.
metadata.name: Bone

metadata.help:
The act of registering to be a user of a service, product or web page.

Related actions:

* [[JoinAction]]: Unlike JoinAction, RegisterAction implies you are registering to be a user of a service, *not* a group/team of people.
* [FollowAction]]: Unlike FollowAction, RegisterAction doesn't imply that the agent is expecting to poll for updates from the object.
* [[SubscribeAction]]: Unlike SubscribeAction, RegisterAction doesn't imply that the agent is expecting updates from the object.
metadata.name: RegisterAction

metadata.help: A restaurant.

metadata.help: Format of this release (the type of recording media used, ie. compact disc, digital media, LP, etc.).
metadata.name: MusicReleaseFormatType

metadata.help: Car repair business.
metadata.name: AutoRepair

metadata.help: A reservation for an event like a concert, sporting event, or lecture.\n\nNote: This type is for information about actual reservations, e.g. in confirmation emails or HTML pages with individual confirmations of reservations. For offers of tickets, use [[Offer]].
metadata.name: EventReservation

metadata.help: A Series in schema.org is a group of related items, typically but not necessarily of the same kind. See also [[CreativeWorkSeries]], [[EventSeries]].
metadata.name: Series

metadata.help: A placeholder for multiple similar products of the same kind.
metadata.name: SomeProducts

inputs.name: inventoryLevel
inputs.help: The current approximate inventory level for the item or items.

metadata.help: A list of possible statuses for the legal force of a legislation.
metadata.name: LegalForceStatus

metadata.help: A step in the instructions for how to achieve a result. It is an ordered list with HowToDirection and/or HowToTip items.
metadata.name: HowToStep

metadata.help: A [[NewsArticle]] providing historical context, definition and detail on a specific topic (aka "explainer" or "backgrounder"). For example, an in-depth article or frequently-asked-questions ([FAQ](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/FAQ)) document on topics such as Climate Change or the European Union. Other kinds of background material from a non-news setting are often described using [[Book]] or [[Article]], in particular [[ScholarlyArticle]]. See also [[NewsArticle]] for related vocabulary from a learning/education perspective.
metadata.name: BackgroundNewsArticle

metadata.help: Any rule set or interactive tool for estimating the risk of developing a complication or condition.
metadata.name: MedicalRiskEstimator

inputs.name: includedRiskFactor
inputs.help: A modifiable or non-modifiable risk factor included in the calculation, e.g. age, coexisting condition.

inputs.name: estimatesRiskOf
inputs.help: The condition, complication, or symptom whose risk is being estimated.

metadata.help: A part of a successively published publication such as a periodical or publication volume, often numbered, usually containing a grouping of works such as articles.\n\nSee also [blog post](http://blog.schema.org/2014/09/schemaorg-support-for-bibliographic_2.html).
metadata.name: PublicationIssue

inputs.name: pageStart
inputs.help: The page on which the work starts; for example "135" or "xiii".

inputs.name: pagination
inputs.help: Any description of pages that is not separated into pageStart and pageEnd; for example, "1-6, 9, 55" or "10-12, 46-49".

inputs.name: pageEnd
inputs.help: The page on which the work ends; for example "138" or "xvi".

inputs.name: issueNumber
inputs.help: Identifies the issue of publication; for example, "iii" or "2".

metadata.help:
The day of the week, e.g. used to specify to which day the opening hours of an OpeningHoursSpecification refer.

Originally, URLs from [GoodRelations](http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1) were used (for [[Monday]], [[Tuesday]], [[Wednesday]], [[Thursday]], [[Friday]], [[Saturday]], [[Sunday]] plus a special entry for [[PublicHolidays]]); these have now been integrated directly into schema.org.
metadata.name: DayOfWeek

metadata.help:
A resort is a place used for relaxation or recreation, attracting visitors for holidays or vacations. Resorts are places, towns or sometimes commercial establishment operated by a single company (Source: Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia, see http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Resort).

See also the dedicated document on the use of schema.org for marking up hotels and other forms of accommodations.
metadata.name: Resort

metadata.help: A service for a vehicle for hire with a driver for local travel. Fares are usually calculated based on distance traveled.

metadata.help: The act of forming one's opinion, reaction or sentiment.

metadata.help: A file containing slides or used for a presentation.

metadata.help: A subclass of OrganizationRole used to describe employee relationships.
metadata.name: EmployeeRole

inputs.name: salaryCurrency
inputs.help: The currency (coded using [ISO 4217](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_4217) ) used for the main salary information in this job posting or for this employee.

inputs.name: baseSalary
inputs.help: The base salary of the job or of an employee in an EmployeeRole.

metadata.help: A tourist attraction.  In principle any Thing can be a [[TouristAttraction]], from a [[Mountain]] and [[LandmarksOrHistoricalBuildings]] to a [[LocalBusiness]].  This Type can be used on its own to describe a general [[TouristAttraction]], or be used as an [[additionalType]] to add tourist attraction properties to any other type.  (See examples below)
metadata.name: TouristAttraction

inputs.name: availableLanguage
inputs.help: A language someone may use with or at the item, service or place. Please use one of the language codes from the [IETF BCP 47 standard](http://tools.ietf.org/html/bcp47). See also [[inLanguage]]

inputs.name: touristType
inputs.help: Attraction suitable for type(s) of tourist. eg. Children, visitors from a particular country, etc.

metadata.help: A reservation for air travel.\n\nNote: This type is for information about actual reservations, e.g. in confirmation emails or HTML pages with individual confirmations of reservations. For offers of tickets, use [[Offer]].
metadata.name: FlightReservation

inputs.name: boardingGroup
inputs.help: The airline-specific indicator of boarding order / preference.

inputs.name: passengerPriorityStatus
inputs.help: The priority status assigned to a passenger for security or boarding (e.g. FastTrack or Priority).

inputs.name: passengerSequenceNumber
inputs.help: The passenger's sequence number as assigned by the airline.

inputs.name: securityScreening

metadata.name: MedicalEnumeration

metadata.help: A web page element, like a table or an image.
metadata.name: WebPageElement

inputs.name: xpath
inputs.help: An XPath, e.g. of a [[SpeakableSpecification]] or [[WebPageElement]]. In the latter case, multiple matches within a page can constitute a single conceptual "Web page element".

inputs.name: cssSelector
inputs.help: A CSS selector, e.g. of a [[SpeakableSpecification]] or [[WebPageElement]]. In the latter case, multiple matches within a page can constitute a single conceptual "Web page element".

metadata.help: Fitness-related activity designed for a specific health-related purpose, including defined exercise routines as well as activity prescribed by a clinician.
metadata.name: ExercisePlan

inputs.name: activityFrequency
inputs.help: How often one should engage in the activity.

inputs.name: restPeriods
inputs.help: How often one should break from the activity.

inputs.name: intensity
inputs.help: Quantitative measure gauging the degree of force involved in the exercise, for example, heartbeats per minute. May include the velocity of the movement.

inputs.name: repetitions
inputs.help: Number of times one should repeat the activity.

inputs.name: workload
inputs.help: Quantitative measure of the physiologic output of the exercise; also referred to as energy expenditure.

inputs.name: exerciseType
inputs.help: Type(s) of exercise or activity, such as strength training, flexibility training, aerobics, cardiac rehabilitation, etc.

inputs.name: activityDuration
inputs.help: Length of time to engage in the activity.

inputs.name: additionalVariable
inputs.help: Any additional component of the exercise prescription that may need to be articulated to the patient. This may include the order of exercises, the number of repetitions of movement, quantitative distance, progressions over time, etc.

metadata.help: An infectious disease is a clinically evident human disease resulting from the presence of pathogenic microbial agents, like pathogenic viruses, pathogenic bacteria, fungi, protozoa, multicellular parasites, and prions. To be considered an infectious disease, such pathogens are known to be able to cause this disease.
metadata.name: InfectiousDisease

inputs.name: transmissionMethod
inputs.help: How the disease spreads, either as a route or vector, for example 'direct contact', 'Aedes aegypti', etc.

inputs.name: infectiousAgent
inputs.help: The actual infectious agent, such as a specific bacterium.

inputs.name: infectiousAgentClass
inputs.help: The class of infectious agent (bacteria, prion, etc.) that causes the disease.

metadata.help:
A FundingScheme combines organizational, project and policy aspects of grant-based funding
    that sets guidelines, principles and mechanisms to support other kinds of projects and activities.
    Funding is typically organized via [[Grant]] funding. Examples of funding schemes: Swiss Priority Programmes (SPPs); EU Framework 7 (FP7); Horizon 2020; the NIH-R01 Grant Program; Wellcome institutional strategic support fund. For large scale public sector funding, the management and administration of grant awards is often handled by other, dedicated, organizations - [[FundingAgency]]s such as ERC, REA, ...
metadata.name: FundingScheme

metadata.help: The mailing address.

inputs.name: addressLocality
inputs.help: The locality in which the street address is, and which is in the region. For example, Mountain View.

inputs.name: streetAddress
inputs.help: The street address. For example, 1600 Amphitheatre Pkwy.

inputs.name: addressCountry
inputs.help: The country. For example, USA. You can also provide the two-letter [ISO 3166-1 alpha-2 country code](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_3166-1).

inputs.name: postOfficeBoxNumber
inputs.help: The post office box number for PO box addresses.

inputs.name: postalCode
inputs.help: The postal code. For example, 94043.

inputs.name: addressRegion
inputs.help: The region in which the locality is, and which is in the country. For example, California or another appropriate first-level [Administrative division](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_administrative_divisions_by_country)

inputs.name: datePosted

metadata.help: The cost per unit of a medical drug. Note that this type is not meant to represent the price in an offer of a drug for sale; see the Offer type for that. This type will typically be used to tag wholesale or average retail cost of a drug, or maximum reimbursable cost. Costs of medical drugs vary widely depending on how and where they are paid for, so while this type captures some of the variables, costs should be used with caution by consumers of this schema's markup.
metadata.name: DrugCost

inputs.name: applicableLocation
inputs.help: The location in which the status applies.

inputs.name: costOrigin
inputs.help: Additional details to capture the origin of the cost data. For example, 'Medicare Part B'.

inputs.name: drugUnit
inputs.help: The unit in which the drug is measured, e.g. '5 mg tablet'.

inputs.name: costCategory
inputs.help: The category of cost, such as wholesale, retail, reimbursement cap, etc.

inputs.name: costPerUnit
inputs.help: The cost per unit of the drug.

inputs.name: costCurrency
inputs.help: The currency (in 3-letter of the drug cost. See: http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_4217

inputs.help: An organization that acknowledges the validity, value or utility of a credential. Note: recognition may include a process of quality assurance or accreditation.

inputs.name: competencyRequired
inputs.help: Knowledge, skill, ability or personal attribute that must be demonstrated by a person or other entity in order to do something such as earn an Educational Occupational Credential or understand a LearningResource.

inputs.name: educationalLevel
inputs.help: The level in terms of progression through an educational or training context. Examples of educational levels include 'beginner', 'intermediate' or 'advanced', and formal sets of level indicators.

metadata.help: The artwork on the outer surface of a CreativeWork.
metadata.name: CoverArt

metadata.help: A ShippingRateSettings represents re-usable pieces of shipping information. It is designed for publication on an URL that may be referenced via the [[shippingSettingsLink]] property of an [[OfferShippingDetails]]. Several occurrences can be published, distinguished and matched (i.e. identified/referenced) by their different values for [[shippingLabel]].
metadata.name: ShippingRateSettings

inputs.name: shippingRate
inputs.help: The shipping rate is the cost of shipping to the specified destination. Typically, the maxValue and currency values (of the [[MonetaryAmount]]) are most appropriate.

inputs.name: freeShippingThreshold
inputs.help: A monetary value above which (or equal to) the shipping rate becomes free. Intended to be used via an [[OfferShippingDetails]] with [[shippingSettingsLink]] matching this [[ShippingRateSettings]].

inputs.name: shippingLabel
inputs.help: Label to match an [[OfferShippingDetails]] with a [[ShippingRateSettings]] (within the context of a [[shippingSettingsLink]] cross-reference).

inputs.name: doesNotShip
inputs.help: Indicates when shipping to a particular [[shippingDestination]] is not available.

inputs.name: shippingDestination
inputs.help: indicates (possibly multiple) shipping destinations. These can be defined in several ways e.g. postalCode ranges.

inputs.name: isUnlabelledFallback
inputs.help: This can be marked 'true' to indicate that some published [[DeliveryTimeSettings]] or [[ShippingRateSettings]] are intended to apply to all [[OfferShippingDetails]] published by the same merchant, when referenced by a [[shippingSettingsLink]] in those settings. It is not meaningful to use a 'true' value for this property alongside a transitTimeLabel (for [[DeliveryTimeSettings]]) or shippingLabel (for [[ShippingRateSettings]]), since this property is for use with unlabelled settings.

metadata.help: Quiz: A test of knowledge, skills and abilities.
metadata.name: Quiz

metadata.help:
The act of an agent communicating (service provider, social media, etc) their arrival by registering/confirming for a previously reserved service (e.g. flight check in) or at a place (e.g. hotel), possibly resulting in a result (boarding pass, etc).

Related actions:

* [[CheckOutAction]]: The antonym of CheckInAction.
* [[ArriveAction]]: Unlike ArriveAction, CheckInAction implies that the agent is informing/confirming the start of a previously reserved service.
* [[ConfirmAction]]: Unlike ConfirmAction, CheckInAction implies that the agent is informing/confirming the *start* of a previously reserved service rather than its validity/existence.
metadata.name: CheckInAction

inputs.help: Languages in which subtitles/captions are available, in [IETF BCP 47 standard format](http://tools.ietf.org/html/bcp47).

inputs.name: partOfTVSeries

inputs.name: titleEIDR
inputs.help:
An [EIDR](https://eidr.org/) (Entertainment Identifier Registry) [[identifier]] representing at the most general/abstract level, a work of film or television.

For example, the motion picture known as "Ghostbusters" has a titleEIDR of  "10.5240/7EC7-228A-510A-053E-CBB8-J". This title (or work) may have several variants, which EIDR calls "edits". See [[editEIDR]].

Since schema.org types like [[Movie]] and [[TVEpisode]] can be used for both works and their multiple expressions, it is possible to use [[titleEIDR]] alone (for a general description), or alongside [[editEIDR]] for a more edit-specific description.

metadata.help: A reservation for lodging at a hotel, motel, inn, etc.\n\nNote: This type is for information about actual reservations, e.g. in confirmation emails or HTML pages with individual confirmations of reservations.
metadata.name: LodgingReservation

inputs.name: lodgingUnitDescription
inputs.help: A full description of the lodging unit.

inputs.name: checkoutTime
inputs.help: The latest someone may check out of a lodging establishment.

inputs.name: lodgingUnitType
inputs.help: Textual description of the unit type (including suite vs. room, size of bed, etc.).

inputs.name: numChildren
inputs.help: The number of children staying in the unit.

inputs.name: checkinTime
inputs.help: The earliest someone may check into a lodging establishment.

inputs.name: numAdults

inputs.name: jurisdiction

inputs.name: cookingMethod

inputs.name: recipeCuisine

inputs.name: nutrition
inputs.help: Nutrition information about the recipe or menu item.

inputs.name: recipeInstructions
inputs.help: A step in making the recipe, in the form of a single item (document, video, etc.) or an ordered list with HowToStep and/or HowToSection items.

inputs.name: cookTime
inputs.help: The time it takes to actually cook the dish, in [ISO 8601 duration format](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_8601).

inputs.name: recipeIngredient
inputs.help: A single ingredient used in the recipe, e.g. sugar, flour or garlic.

inputs.name: suitableForDiet
inputs.help: Indicates a dietary restriction or guideline for which this recipe or menu item is suitable, e.g. diabetic, halal etc.

inputs.name: ingredients

inputs.name: recipeCategory
inputs.help: The category of the recipefor example, appetizer, entree, etc.

inputs.name: recipeYield
inputs.help: The quantity produced by the recipe (for example, number of people served, number of servings, etc).

metadata.help: EnergyConsumptionDetails represents information related to the energy efficiency of a product that consumes energy. The information that can be provided is based on international regulations such as for example [EU directive 2017/1369](https://eur-lex.europa.eu/eli/reg/2017/1369/oj) for energy labeling and the [Energy labeling rule](https://www.ftc.gov/enforcement/rules/rulemaking-regulatory-reform-proceedings/energy-water-use-labeling-consumer) under the Energy Policy and Conservation Act (EPCA) in the US
metadata.name: EnergyConsumptionDetails

inputs.name: energyEfficiencyScaleMin
inputs.help: Specifies the least energy efficient class on the regulated EU energy consumption scale for the product category a product belongs to. For example, energy consumption for televisions placed on the market after January 1, 2020 is scaled from D to A+++.

inputs.name: hasEnergyEfficiencyCategory
inputs.help: Defines the energy efficiency Category (which could be either a rating out of range of values or a yes/no certification) for a product according to an international energy efficiency standard

inputs.name: energyEfficiencyScaleMax
inputs.help: Specifies the most energy efficient class on the regulated EU energy consumption scale for the product category a product belongs to. For example, energy consumption for televisions placed on the market after January 1, 2020 is scaled from D to A+++.

metadata.name: Distance

metadata.help: A vehicle is a device that is designed or used to transport people or cargo over land, water, air, or through space.
metadata.name: Vehicle

inputs.name: productionDate
inputs.help: The date of production of the item, e.g. vehicle.

inputs.name: fuelConsumption
inputs.help:
The amount of fuel consumed for traveling a particular distance or temporal duration with the given vehicle (e.g. liters per 100 km).

* Note 1: There are unfortunately no standard unit codes for liters per 100 km.  Use [[unitText]] to indicate the unit of measurement, e.g. L/100 km.
* Note 2: There are two ways of indicating the fuel consumption, [[fuelConsumption]] (e.g. 8 liters per 100 km) and [[fuelEfficiency]] (e.g. 30 miles per gallon). They are reciprocal.
* Note 3: Often, the absolute value is useful only when related to driving speed ("at 80 km/h") or usage pattern ("city traffic"). You can use [[valueReference]] to link the value for the fuel consumption to another value.

inputs.name: vehicleConfiguration
inputs.help: A short text indicating the configuration of the vehicle, e.g. '5dr hatchback ST 2.5 MT 225 hp' or 'limited edition'.

inputs.name: vehicleSpecialUsage
inputs.help: Indicates whether the vehicle has been used for special purposes, like commercial rental, driving school, or as a taxi. The legislation in many countries requires this information to be revealed when offering a car for sale.

inputs.name: speed
inputs.help:
The speed range of the vehicle. If the vehicle is powered by an engine, the upper limit of the speed range (indicated by [[maxValue]] should be the maximum speed achievable under regular conditions.

Typical unit code(s): KMH for km/h, HM for mile per hour (0.447 04 m/s), KNT for knot

*Note 1: Use [[minValue]] and [[maxValue]] to indicate the range. Typically, the minimal value is zero.
* Note 2: There are many different ways of measuring the speed range. You can link to information about how the given value has been determined using the [[valueReference]] property.

inputs.name: modelDate
inputs.help: The release date of a vehicle model (often used to differentiate versions of the same make and model).

inputs.name: wheelbase
inputs.help: The distance between the centers of the front and rear wheels.\n\nTypical unit code(s): CMT for centimeters, MTR for meters, INH for inches, FOT for foot/feet

inputs.name: vehicleSeatingCapacity
inputs.help: The number of passengers that can be seated in the vehicle, both in terms of the physical space available, and in terms of limitations set by law.\n\nTypical unit code(s): C62 for persons.

inputs.name: steeringPosition
inputs.help: The position of the steering wheel or similar device (mostly for cars).

inputs.name: accelerationTime
inputs.help:
The time needed to accelerate the vehicle from a given start velocity to a given target velocity.

Typical unit code(s): SEC for seconds

* Note: There are unfortunately no standard unit codes for seconds/0..100 km/h or seconds/0..60 mph. Simply use "SEC" for seconds and indicate the velocities in the [[name]] of the [[QuantitativeValue]], or use [[valueReference]] with a [[QuantitativeValue]] of 0..60 mph or 0..100 km/h to specify the reference speeds.

inputs.name: fuelEfficiency
inputs.help:
The distance traveled per unit of fuel used; most commonly miles per gallon (mpg) or kilometers per liter (km/L).

* Note 1: There are unfortunately no standard unit codes for miles per gallon or kilometers per liter. Use [[unitText]] to indicate the unit of measurement, e.g. mpg or km/L.
* Note 2: There are two ways of indicating the fuel consumption, [[fuelConsumption]] (e.g. 8 liters per 100 km) and [[fuelEfficiency]] (e.g. 30 miles per gallon). They are reciprocal.
* Note 3: Often, the absolute value is useful only when related to driving speed ("at 80 km/h") or usage pattern ("city traffic"). You can use [[valueReference]] to link the value for the fuel economy to another value.

inputs.name: vehicleInteriorType
inputs.help: The type or material of the interior of the vehicle (e.g. synthetic fabric, leather, wood, etc.). While most interior types are characterized by the material used, an interior type can also be based on vehicle usage or target audience.

inputs.name: vehicleIdentificationNumber
inputs.help: The Vehicle Identification Number (VIN) is a unique serial number used by the automotive industry to identify individual motor vehicles.

inputs.name: vehicleInteriorColor
inputs.help: The color or color combination of the interior of the vehicle.

inputs.name: dateVehicleFirstRegistered
inputs.help: The date of the first registration of the vehicle with the respective public authorities.

inputs.name: emissionsCO2
inputs.help: The CO2 emissions in g/km. When used in combination with a QuantitativeValue, put "g/km" into the unitText property of that value, since there is no UN/CEFACT Common Code for "g/km".

inputs.name: mileageFromOdometer
inputs.help: The total distance travelled by the particular vehicle since its initial production, as read from its odometer.\n\nTypical unit code(s): KMT for kilometers, SMI for statute miles

inputs.name: trailerWeight
inputs.help:
The permitted weight of a trailer attached to the vehicle.

Typical unit code(s): KGM for kilogram, LBR for pound
* Note 1: You can indicate additional information in the [[name]] of the [[QuantitativeValue]] node.
* Note 2: You may also link to a [[QualitativeValue]] node that provides additional information using [[valueReference]].
* Note 3: Note that you can use [[minValue]] and [[maxValue]] to indicate ranges.

inputs.name: fuelCapacity
inputs.help: The capacity of the fuel tank or in the case of electric cars, the battery. If there are multiple components for storage, this should indicate the total of all storage of the same type.\n\nTypical unit code(s): LTR for liters, GLL of US gallons, GLI for UK / imperial gallons, AMH for ampere-hours (for electrical vehicles).

inputs.name: vehicleTransmission
inputs.help: The type of component used for transmitting the power from a rotating power source to the wheels or other relevant component(s) ("gearbox" for cars).

inputs.name: numberOfDoors
inputs.help: The number of doors.\n\nTypical unit code(s): C62

inputs.name: meetsEmissionStandard
inputs.help: Indicates that the vehicle meets the respective emission standard.

inputs.name: knownVehicleDamages
inputs.help: A textual description of known damages, both repaired and unrepaired.

inputs.name: weightTotal
inputs.help:
The permitted total weight of the loaded vehicle, including passengers and cargo and the weight of the empty vehicle.

Typical unit code(s): KGM for kilogram, LBR for pound

* Note 1: You can indicate additional information in the [[name]] of the [[QuantitativeValue]] node.
* Note 2: You may also link to a [[QualitativeValue]] node that provides additional information using [[valueReference]].
* Note 3: Note that you can use [[minValue]] and [[maxValue]] to indicate ranges.

inputs.name: vehicleEngine
inputs.help: Information about the engine or engines of the vehicle.

inputs.name: cargoVolume
inputs.help:
The available volume for cargo or luggage. For automobiles, this is usually the trunk volume.

Typical unit code(s): LTR for liters, FTQ for cubic foot/feet

Note: You can use [[minValue]] and [[maxValue]] to indicate ranges.

inputs.name: seatingCapacity
inputs.help: The number of persons that can be seated (e.g. in a vehicle), both in terms of the physical space available, and in terms of limitations set by law.\n\nTypical unit code(s): C62 for persons

inputs.name: tongueWeight
inputs.help:
The permitted vertical load (TWR) of a trailer attached to the vehicle. Also referred to as Tongue Load Rating (TLR) or Vertical Load Rating (VLR)

Typical unit code(s): KGM for kilogram, LBR for pound

* Note 1: You can indicate additional information in the [[name]] of the [[QuantitativeValue]] node.
* Note 2: You may also link to a [[QualitativeValue]] node that provides additional information using [[valueReference]].
* Note 3: Note that you can use [[minValue]] and [[maxValue]] to indicate ranges.

inputs.name: callSign
inputs.help: A [callsign](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Call_sign), as used in broadcasting and radio communications to identify people, radio and TV stations, or vehicles.

inputs.name: fuelType
inputs.help: The type of fuel suitable for the engine or engines of the vehicle. If the vehicle has only one engine, this property can be attached directly to the vehicle.

inputs.name: numberOfForwardGears
inputs.help: The total number of forward gears available for the transmission system of the vehicle.\n\nTypical unit code(s): C62

inputs.name: numberOfPreviousOwners
inputs.help: The number of owners of the vehicle, including the current one.\n\nTypical unit code(s): C62

inputs.name: numberOfAirbags
inputs.help: The number or type of airbags in the vehicle.

inputs.name: bodyType
inputs.help: Indicates the design and body style of the vehicle (e.g. station wagon, hatchback, etc.).

inputs.name: driveWheelConfiguration
inputs.help: The drive wheel configuration, i.e. which roadwheels will receive torque from the vehicle's engine via the drivetrain.

inputs.name: purchaseDate
inputs.help: The date the item e.g. vehicle was purchased by the current owner.

inputs.name: payload
inputs.help:
The permitted weight of passengers and cargo, EXCLUDING the weight of the empty vehicle.

Typical unit code(s): KGM for kilogram, LBR for pound

* Note 1: Many databases specify the permitted TOTAL weight instead, which is the sum of [[weight]] and [[payload]]
* Note 2: You can indicate additional information in the [[name]] of the [[QuantitativeValue]] node.
* Note 3: You may also link to a [[QualitativeValue]] node that provides additional information using [[valueReference]].
* Note 4: Note that you can use [[minValue]] and [[maxValue]] to indicate ranges.

inputs.name: vehicleModelDate
inputs.help: The release date of a vehicle model (often used to differentiate versions of the same make and model).

inputs.name: numberOfAxles
inputs.help: The number of axles.\n\nTypical unit code(s): C62

metadata.help: A scholarly article.
metadata.name: ScholarlyArticle

metadata.help: A compound price specification is one that bundles multiple prices that all apply in combination for different dimensions of consumption. Use the name property of the attached unit price specification for indicating the dimension of a price component (e.g. "electricity" or "final cleaning").
metadata.name: CompoundPriceSpecification

inputs.name: priceComponent
inputs.help: This property links to all [[UnitPriceSpecification]] nodes that apply in parallel for the [[CompoundPriceSpecification]] node.

inputs.name: priceType
inputs.help: Defines the type of a price specified for an offered product, for example a list price, a (temporary) sale price or a manufacturer suggested retail price. If multiple prices are specified for an offer the [[priceType]] property can be used to identify the type of each such specified price. The value of priceType can be specified as a value from enumeration PriceTypeEnumeration or as a free form text string for price types that are not already predefined in PriceTypeEnumeration.

metadata.help: A media object, such as an image, video, or audio object embedded in a web page or a downloadable dataset i.e. DataDownload. Note that a creative work may have many media objects associated with it on the same web page. For example, a page about a single song (MusicRecording) may have a music video (VideoObject), and a high and low bandwidth audio stream (2 AudioObject's).
metadata.name: File

inputs.name: associatedArticle
inputs.help: A NewsArticle associated with the Media Object.

inputs.name: regionsAllowed
inputs.help: The regions where the media is allowed. If not specified, then it's assumed to be allowed everywhere. Specify the countries in [ISO 3166 format](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_3166).

inputs.name: contentUrl
inputs.help: Actual bytes of the media object, for example the image file or video file.

inputs.name: playerType
inputs.help: Player type required—for example, Flash or Silverlight.

inputs.name: productionCompany
inputs.help: The production company or studio responsible for the item e.g. series, video game, episode etc.

inputs.name: embedUrl
inputs.help: A URL pointing to a player for a specific video. In general, this is the information in the ```src``` element of an ```embed``` tag and should not be the same as the content of the ```loc``` tag.

inputs.name: requiresSubscription
inputs.help: Indicates if use of the media require a subscription  (either paid or free). Allowed values are ```true``` or ```false``` (note that an earlier version had 'yes', 'no').

inputs.name: duration
inputs.help: The duration of the item (movie, audio recording, event, etc.) in [ISO 8601 date format](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_8601).

inputs.name: height
inputs.help: The height of the item.

inputs.name: endTime
inputs.help: The endTime of something. For a reserved event or service (e.g. FoodEstablishmentReservation), the time that it is expected to end. For actions that span a period of time, when the action was performed. e.g. John wrote a book from January to *December*. For media, including audio and video, it's the time offset of the end of a clip within a larger file.\n\nNote that Event uses startDate/endDate instead of startTime/endTime, even when describing dates with times. This situation may be clarified in future revisions.

inputs.name: width
inputs.help: The width of the item.

inputs.name: encodesCreativeWork
inputs.help: The CreativeWork encoded by this media object.

inputs.name: contentSize
inputs.help: File size in (mega/kilo) bytes.

inputs.name: bitrate
inputs.help: The bitrate of the media object.

inputs.name: encodingFormat
inputs.help:
Media type typically expressed using a MIME format (see [IANA site](http://www.iana.org/assignments/media-types/media-types.xhtml) and [MDN reference](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTTP/Basics_of_HTTP/MIME_types)) e.g. application/zip for a SoftwareApplication binary, audio/mpeg for .mp3 etc.).

In cases where a [[CreativeWork]] has several media type representations, [[encoding]] can be used to indicate each [[MediaObject]] alongside particular [[encodingFormat]] information.

Unregistered or niche encoding and file formats can be indicated instead via the most appropriate URL, e.g. defining Web page or a Wikipedia/Wikidata entry.

inputs.name: startTime
inputs.help: The startTime of something. For a reserved event or service (e.g. FoodEstablishmentReservation), the time that it is expected to start. For actions that span a period of time, when the action was performed. e.g. John wrote a book from *January* to December. For media, including audio and video, it's the time offset of the start of a clip within a larger file.\n\nNote that Event uses startDate/endDate instead of startTime/endTime, even when describing dates with times. This situation may be clarified in future revisions.

inputs.name: uploadDate
inputs.help: Date when this media object was uploaded to this site.

metadata.help: A food-related business.
metadata.name: FoodEstablishment

inputs.name: servesCuisine
inputs.help: The cuisine of the restaurant.

inputs.name: hasMenu
inputs.help: Either the actual menu as a structured representation, as text, or a URL of the menu.

inputs.name: acceptsReservations
inputs.help: Indicates whether a FoodEstablishment accepts reservations. Values can be Boolean, an URL at which reservations can be made or (for backwards compatibility) the strings ```Yes``` or ```No```.

inputs.name: starRating
inputs.help: An official rating for a lodging business or food establishment, e.g. from national associations or standards bodies. Use the author property to indicate the rating organization, e.g. as an Organization with name such as (e.g. HOTREC, DEHOGA, WHR, or Hotelstars).

inputs.name: menu
inputs.help: Either the actual menu as a structured representation, as text, or a URL of the menu.

metadata.help: A process of care used in either a diagnostic, therapeutic, preventive or palliative capacity that relies on invasive (surgical), non-invasive, or other techniques.
metadata.name: MedicalProcedure

inputs.name: bodyLocation
inputs.help: Location in the body of the anatomical structure.

inputs.name: followup
inputs.help: Typical or recommended followup care after the procedure is performed.

inputs.name: procedureType
inputs.help: The type of procedure, for example Surgical, Noninvasive, or Percutaneous.

inputs.name: preparation
inputs.help: Typical preparation that a patient must undergo before having the procedure performed.

inputs.name: status
inputs.help: The status of the study (enumerated).

inputs.name: howPerformed
inputs.help: How the procedure is performed.

metadata.help:
A meeting room, conference room, or conference hall is a room provided for singular events such as business conferences and meetings (Source: Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia, see http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Conference_hall).

See also the dedicated document on the use of schema.org for marking up hotels and other forms of accommodations.
metadata.name: MeetingRoom

metadata.help: An audiobook.
metadata.name: Audiobook

inputs.name: readBy

metadata.help: Anatomical features that can be observed by sight (without dissection), including the form and proportions of the human body as well as surface landmarks that correspond to deeper subcutaneous structures. Superficial anatomy plays an important role in sports medicine, phlebotomy, and other medical specialties as underlying anatomical structures can be identified through surface palpation. For example, during back surgery, superficial anatomy can be used to palpate and count vertebrae to find the site of incision. Or in phlebotomy, superficial anatomy can be used to locate an underlying vein; for example, the median cubital vein can be located by palpating the borders of the cubital fossa (such as the epicondyles of the humerus) and then looking for the superficial signs of the vein, such as size, prominence, ability to refill after depression, and feel of surrounding tissue support. As another example, in a subluxation (dislocation) of the glenohumeral joint, the bony structure becomes pronounced with the deltoid muscle failing to cover the glenohumeral joint allowing the edges of the scapula to be superficially visible. Here, the superficial anatomy is the visible edges of the scapula, implying the underlying dislocation of the joint (the related anatomical structure).
metadata.name: SuperficialAnatomy

inputs.name: associatedPathophysiology
inputs.help: If applicable, a description of the pathophysiology associated with the anatomical system, including potential abnormal changes in the mechanical, physical, and biochemical functions of the system.

inputs.name: relatedAnatomy
inputs.help: Anatomical systems or structures that relate to the superficial anatomy.

inputs.name: relatedCondition
inputs.help: A medical condition associated with this anatomy.

inputs.name: relatedTherapy
inputs.help: A medical therapy related to this anatomy.

inputs.name: significance
inputs.help: The significance associated with the superficial anatomy; as an example, how characteristics of the superficial anatomy can suggest underlying medical conditions or courses of treatment.

inputs.name: applicationContact
inputs.help: Contact details for further information relevant to this job posting.

inputs.help: The typical working hours for this job (e.g. 1st shift, night shift, 8am-5pm).
